# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bermondsey
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bermondsey/020] The 020 area code fully replaced older area codes for London on 22 April 2000, following multiple telephone number changes during the 1990s.
[src:bermondsey/020] As is the case for other codes in the UK, the 020 area code may also be used for services without any physical presence in the area, such as private networks or virtual numbering.
[src:bermondsey/020] One such user is the Foreign and Commonwealth Office Telecommunications Network, provided by Global Crossing, 020 is also one of the dialling codes used for telephone services on the remote South Atlantic island of Tristan da Cunha.
[src:bermondsey/020] Before the introduction of national dialling codes, the area now served by 020 had a large multiple telephone exchange system, called the London telephone area.
[src:bermondsey/020] The first exchange in this area, Central, was opened in the City of London on 1 March 1902.
[src:bermondsey/020] The Director telephone system was developed so that subscribers in London could call one another in a linked numbering scheme regardless of whether they were on a manual local exchange or an automatic one.
[src:bermondsey/020] In 1927, Holborn, the first Director automatic exchange in London, was cut over to the new system at midnight on Saturday 12 November.
[src:bermondsey/020] Because it was mainly a business exchange, most subscribers did not use the new system until Monday 14 November.
[src:bermondsey/020] The successful changeover was delayed by subscribers' unfamiliarity with dialling.
[src:bermondsey/020] Bishopgate and Sloane exchanges followed in six weeks, after which came Western and Monument exchanges.
[src:bermondsey/020] Because the London area contained 80 exchanges, complete conversion took many years.
[src:bermondsey/020] By 1934, the London telephone area comprised all 147 exchanges within 12+1⁄2 miles (20 km) of Oxford Circus.
[src:bermondsey/020] By 1950, the London Director system had 75 exchanges within a 5-mile (8 km) radius of Oxford Circus and a further 65 in the 5–10-mile (8–16 km) belt.
[src:bermondsey/020] In Greater London (in other words, within 20 miles (32 km) of Oxford Circus), there were 237 exchanges.
[src:bermondsey/020] In January 1956 a new director exchange – "SKYport" – was opened at London Heathrow Airport.
[src:bermondsey/020] From 1922, the first three digits of a seven-digit subscriber number – in other words, the local exchange codes – were represented with letters by way of a mnemonic.
[src:bermondsey/020] Each three-character code corresponded to an exchange within the London telephone area.
[src:bermondsey/020] The subscriber numbers were written, for example, as "ABBey 1234" and "WIMbledon 1234" or "ABB 1234" and "WIM 1234".
[src:bermondsey/020] By 1965, there were 350 local exchanges in London and the number of permutations that could be used for exchange names had been exhausted.
[src:bermondsey/020] With the change to all-figure dialling in 1966, the system of mnemonics was withdrawn and the three-digit local exchange codes of many subscribers were altered.
[src:bermondsey/020] The old codes continued to work in parallel with new codes until January 1970, when the "ANN: All-figure Numbers Now" advertising campaign prompted callers to use only the new codes.
[src:bermondsey/020] The transition to all-figure dialling allowed the codes to be grouped into eight sectors; all exchanges within 6 kilometres (3.7 mi) of the centre of London formed the Central sector and the other sectors radiated from it.
[src:bermondsey/020] The first three digits of a subscriber number continued to indicate the exchange to which the number belonged; for example, "222 1234" was in Westminster (Central Sector) and "946 1234" in Wimbledon (South West Sector).
[src:bermondsey/020] More than one local exchange code was usually overlaid for each area, so all Wimbledon numbers did not necessarily begin "946".
[src:bermondsey/020] Subscriber numbers changed to eight digits in 2000 when an additional 7 or 8 was added to each local exchange code (for example, "7222 1234" in Westminster and "8946 1234" in Wimbledon).
[src:bermondsey/020] The STD code 01 was assigned to the London telephone area on 6 April 1959 as part of preparations for subscriber trunk dialling.
[src:bermondsey/020] For the next thirty years, "01" became synonymous with the capital.
[src:bermondsey/020] Until May 1990, the 01 code covered the same area as the current 020 code and had capacity for fewer than 10 million telephone numbers.
[src:bermondsey/020] In May 1990, the 01 code was abandoned and the area divided between 071 – which covered exchanges in the Central sector – and 081, which covered all other sectors.
[src:bermondsey/020] Exceptionally, two exchanges in the East sector covering the London Docklands redevelopment area were assigned the 071 code.
[src:bermondsey/020] The anticipation that the code associated with central districts would be more prestigious than the other associated with the outer suburbs was used as a plot device in the Essex-based TV comedy series *Birds of a Feather*.
[src:bermondsey/020] At the time of the split, there were five local exchange codes assigned to Mercury Communications and numbers in these ranges could be assigned to either code.
[src:bermondsey/020] This area code split doubled the potential capacity.
[src:bermondsey/020] In 1995, on "PhONEday", the codes changed again, to 0171 and 0181.
[src:bermondsey/020] The split into two area codes only lasted a decade.
[src:bermondsey/020] As part of the Big Number Change on 22 April 2000, the 0171 and 0181 codes were replaced with 020, following a period of dual-running that began on 1 June 1999 when the new 020 code was activated and ended on 14 October 2000 when the old 0171 and 0181 codes were finally ceased.
[src:bermondsey/020] The 22 April 2000 change also affected subscriber local numbers which gained an extra digit.
[src:bermondsey/020] As a result of this history, there is now a widespread misconception that 0207 and 0208 are the dialling codes for parts of London.
[src:bermondsey/020] This was exacerbated when local numbers beginning 3 started to be issued.
[src:bermondsey/020] The reunification under a single code created capacity for approaching 100 million telephone numbers and, starting in 2005, subscriber numbers beginning with the digit "3" were issued alongside those beginning "7" and "8".
[src:bermondsey/020] In August 2019, Ofcom announced that subscriber numbers beginning with the digit "4" will also be introduced.
[src:bermondsey/020] The London telephone area operated as a single group for charging purposes in which all calls were priced at local rate.
[src:bermondsey/020] Additionally, as was usual, calls to and from the adjacent charge groups were charged as local.
[src:bermondsey/020] The code serves a roughly circular area with a radius of 12 miles from the centre of London.
[src:bermondsey/020] The Greater London boundary varies from 11 miles to 20 miles from the centre and consequently some outer districts are covered by adjacent codes and in some places the 020 code extends beyond the Greater London boundary.
[src:bermondsey/020] The code covers an area larger than the London post town where letters addressed to "LONDON" are delivered.
[src:bermondsey/020] The City of London and at least some part of all 32 London boroughs are within the 020 area code.
[src:bermondsey/020] There are six exchanges outside Greater London that use the 020 code.
[src:bermondsey/020] Communities outside Greater London that are within the code are Buckhurst Hill, Chigwell, Loughton and Sewardstone in Essex; Borehamwood, Bushey, Carpenders Park, Elstree and South Oxhey in Hertfordshire; and Ewell, Molesey, Thames Ditton and Whyteleafe in Surrey.
[src:bermondsey/020] There are eighteen exchanges within Greater London that do not use the 020 code.
[src:bermondsey/020] With the introduction of the (020) area code, as part of the Big Number Change, subscriber numbers were changed from 7-digits (xxx xxxx) to 8-digits (xxxx xxxx).
[src:bermondsey/020] This allowed new ranges of numbers to be issued.
[src:bermondsey/020] In 2006 59% of numbers within the 020 code were allocated to BT.
[src:bermondsey/020] The area code is not subject to number conservation and the regulator Ofcom does not restrict the size of number blocks that are allocated.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] The **12th (Service) Battalion, East Surrey Regiment (Bermondsey)** (12th East Surreys or 12th ESR) was an infantry unit recruited as part of 'Kitchener's Army' in World War I.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] It was raised in the summer of 1915 by the Mayor and Borough of Bermondsey in South East London.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] It served on the Western Front from May 1916, seeing action at the Battle of Flers–Courcelette when it famously followed one of the first tanks down the high street.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] After a period on the Italian Front it returned to the west to serve against the German spring offensive.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] Lastly, it took part in the final advance to victory in Flanders, before participating in the Allied occupation of the Rhineland.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] On 6 August 1914, less than 48 hours after Britain's declaration of war, Parliament sanctioned an increase of 500,000 men for the Regular British Army.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] The newly appointed Secretary of State for War, Earl Kitchener of Khartoum, issued his famous call to arms: 'Your King and Country Need You', urging the first 100,000 volunteers to come forward.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] Men flooded into the recruiting offices and the 'first hundred thousand' were enlisted within days.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] This group of six divisions with supporting arms became known as Kitchener's First New Army, or 'K1'.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] The K2, K3 and K4 battalions, brigades and divisions followed soon afterwards.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] But the flood of volunteers overwhelmed the ability of the Army to absorb them, and the K5 units were largely raised by local initiative rather than at regimental depots, often from men from particular localities or backgrounds who wished to serve together: these were known as 'Pals battalions'.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] The 'Pals' phenomenon quickly spread across the country, as local recruiting committees offered complete units to the War Office (WO).
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] Encouraged by this response, in February 1915 Kitchener approached the 28 Metropolitan Borough Councils in the County of London, and the 'Great Metropolitan Recruiting Campaign' went ahead in April, with each mayor asked to raise a unit of local men.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] Kitchener's request was discussed by Bermondsey Borough Council on 4 May.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] There was some opposition on the grounds that the borough already hosted the 22nd (County of London) Battalion, London Regiment (The Queen's), a pre-war Territorial Force (TF) unit with its drill hall at Jamaica Road.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] This unit had quickly expanded to three battalions after the outbreak of war and continued to recruit in the borough.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] Nevertheless, the council resolved to raise a Bermondsey Battalion: this became the **12th (Service) Battalion, East Surrey Regiment.** (The East Surrey Regiment was the Regular Army regiment covering South London, while the London Regiment consisted entirely of part-time soldiers of the TF).
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] WO authorisation was issued on14 May, recruiting began immediately, and the battalion was officially formed on 24 May.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] Battalion Headquarters (HQ) was established at the Town Hall, and the Oval in Southwark Park was used for drill.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] Beatson, formerly of the Royal Warwickshire Regiment, was appointed as the first commanding officer (CO).
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] A number of other officers came from the Inns of Court Officers Training Corps, and Beatson borrowed non-commissioned officers (NCOs) from the depot and 3rd (Reserve) Bn of the East Surreys to carry out initial training.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] By then over 500 men had been recruited and took part in the parade.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] Soon the number swelled to over 1000, mainly workers from the docks, the riverside and the tanneries in Rotherhithe, though these included significant numbers who were under- or over-age or unfit, and later had to be discharged or transferred to reserve units.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] At first the men lived at home or were billeted locally.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] The Mayor, John Hart, suggested that the battalion should have a distinctive cap badge incorporating the borough's coat of arms, as was done by the 13th East Surreys, recruited in Wandsworth.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] Lieutenant-Col Beatson refused, arguing that they were a battalion of a famous regiment and should wear its badge.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] As a compromise the Bermondsey battalion wore distinctive collar badges supplied by the borough and authorised by the WO.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] On 2 October 1915 the battalion marched from Rotherhithe to Waterloo Station and entrained for Milford Station in Surrey.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] It then marched into Witley Camp to join 41st Division, the last 'K' division to be formed.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] It was assigned to 122nd Brigade, serving alongside the 15th (S) Bn, Hampshire Regiment (2nd Portsmouth) ('15th Hants', the 'Pompey Pals'), 11th (S) Bn, Queen's Own Royal West Kent Regiment (Lewisham) ('11th RWK') and 18th (S) Bn, King's Royal Rifle Corps (Arts & Crafts) ('18th KRRC').
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] The battalions at Witley were equipped with Lee-Enfield Mark III rifles, specialists such as Lewis gunners, signallers and 'bombers' were selected and trained.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] Route marches were carried out with full kit, the pouches filled with iron weights (known as 'Kitchener's chocolate') to simulate the weight of ammunition; the men of 12th East Surreys were among those guilty of discarding these weights in roadside ditches.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] Unfit personnel were transferred to the 3rd and 14th Reserve battalions, and replaced with trained men from them and from the 10th and 11th Reserve battalions.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] On 8 November 12th ESR marched to Oudenarde Barracks at Aldershot, where the men fired their musketry courses, before returning to Witley.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] On 14 February 1916 the battalion returned to Aldershot to begin final intensive training prior to going overseas to join the British Expeditionary Force (BEF) on the Western Front.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] Lieutenant-Col Beatson was replaced by a younger man, Major H.H.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] Lee of the Cameronians, who had been wounded on the Western Front and was now promoted to take over command.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] The 14th (Reserve) Battalion, East Surrey Regiment, was formed in Wandsworth in the summer of 1915 from the depot companies of 12th (Bermondsey) and 13th (Wandsworth) Bns as a Local Reserve battalion to supply reinforcement drafts to the two service battalions.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] In practice the majority of the men came from the surplus recruits to the Wandsworth Bn, whose first commanding officer transferred across to command it.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] On 1 November, when it had reached a strength of between 500 and 600 men it went to Gravesend, where it joined 26th Reserve Brigade.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p01] However, on 26 June 1916 it was absorbed into the other battalions of 26th Reserve Bde.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 1 May 12th East Surreys entrained at Farnborough for Southampton Docks, where the men embarked on the transport *Caesarea* and landed at Le Havre in France the following morning with a strength of 1018 officers and men.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 4 May the battalion went by train to Goodearsveldt and then marched to billets at Outtersteene in the division's concentration area west of Bailleul in Second Army's area.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] While continuing its training, parties from the new division were sent up to the line for instruction in trench warfare from experienced units.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Fifty-strong parties from 12th ESR were attached to units of 9th (Scottish) Division in Ploegsteert Wood ('Plugstreet Wood') for 48 hours each.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 13 May the enemy raided 6th King's Own Scottish Borderers to which one of 12th ESR's parties was currently attached.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Although the enemy put down a heavy barrage and some of the parapets were caved in, the East Surrey party suffered no casualties.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The battalion also had to supply working parties, and it began to suffer a trickle of casualties, particularly from chance shelling or trench mortar fire or random machine gun fire, or during patrolling or trench raids.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] When 41st Division arrived on the Western Front the BEF was preparing for that summer's 'Big Push', the Battle of the Somme, the bombardment beginning on 24 June.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] To confuse the enemy as to the extent of the offensive, 41st Division was ordered to make diversionary raids at Ploegsteert.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 122nd Brigade's raid was preceded by its own lengthy bombardment, and during those days the infantry battalions carried up over 1000 gas cylinders and installed them along the division's front.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The final bombardment began on the morning of 30 June, and the Germans retaliated strongly, causing considerable damage and numerous casualties.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The British bombardment rose to full intensity at 21.15, and the gas was released at 22.00.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 122nd Brigade's raiding parties went out just before 22.30: 12th ESR's raiders (2 officers and 34 other ranks (ORs)) had a feature known as 'The Fort' as their objective.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] They crossed No man's land without difficulty (the only party from 122nd Bde who succeeded) and entered the Fort, finding the strongpoint badly battered by the shelling and abandoned by the enemy.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Several of the battalion's most skilful raiders were pre-war members of Bermondsey's notorious 'Black Hand Gang', who left a signboard bearing a black hand in the Fort before retiring (the name was later sometimes applied to the whole battalion).
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Although the raiding party only had four casualties, the battalion suffered numerous others from the day's counter-bombardment.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] It was relieved by 10th Queen's at 05.00 next morning and went back to billets at Soyer Farm.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The real offensive began that day (1 July) but did not involve the Ploegsteert sector, where 41st Division continued normal trench duty and preparing for a new gas attack.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Lieutenant-Col Lee was wounded by shellfire on the night of 13/14 July and the second-in-command, Maj H.J.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Walmisley-Dresser, assumed command of 12th ESR as acting Lt-Col (he was from the Royal Warwickshire Regiment and had served with Paget's Horse during the Second Boer War).
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 15 August 12th ESR left Soyer Farm and went by stages to Thieushouck, where it began special training before 41st Division joined in the offensive.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] It moved on 23 August to Mouflers, where the training included operating in a wood similar to the notorious Delville Wood on the Somme.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] A Company and two sections of Lewis gunners took part in demonstrations for officers and NCOs attending Fourth Army Trench Warfare School at Flixecourt.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Finally, on 6 September the whole battalion entrained at Longpré-les-Corps-Saints station for Méricourt-l'Abbé, then marched to bivouacs at Fricourt, which had been captured at the beginning of the Somme Offensive.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 41st Division was now ordered to take part in the next phase of the offensive, the Battle of Flers-Courcelette, in which 122nd Bde on the division's left was to capture the village of Flers.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] For this its first attack, 41st Division had support from tanks, also making their first ever appearance on a battlefield.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Ten Mark I tanks of D Company, Heavy Section, Machine Gun Corps, were assigned to the division, formed up behind the infantry.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 12th ESR was in the brigade's second line, following 18th KRRC, and took up its positions in the north-west corner of Delville Wood by 02.00 on 15 September, with a battle strength of 17 officers and 634 ORs.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Walmisley-Dresser's orders for the attack were that the battalion would advance in four waves on a four-company front, moving off in successive lines of half-platoons in file.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] While the tanks crept into position behind them, the half-platoons sheltered in shell-holes, under intermittent shelling with lachrymatory gas, until Zero at 06.20.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] At Zero the whole brigade moved forward behind a Creeping barrage.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] As 18th KRRC quickly took the first objective, 'Switch Trench', 12th ESR moved into the old British front line trench and paused.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] It then set off behind 18th KRRC, suffering numerous casualties as German machine guns in Flers swept the old No man's land.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] By the time the first waves reached Switch Trench they were becoming mixed up with 18th KRRC.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Moving fast, the two battalions reached the second objective ('Flers Trench') after about 1,000 yards (910 m).
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] One machine gun team in the trench caused heavy casualties to A Company before they were rushed with the bayonet, otherwise the Germans surrendered to the Company Sergeant-Major who had succeeded to the command of A Company.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The advance had been so fast that 18th KRRC and 12th ESR were now in front of their own creeping barrage.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The signallers showed flares and coloured panels to alert the contact aircraft overhead, who ordered the artillery to lift the barrage forwards.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] While the battalion waited in Flers trench, the first of the tanks (D16, *Dracula*) arrived, and when the barrage lifted onto Flers they went forward together over the last 600 yards (550 m) to the village, the tanks flattening the German barbed wire.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Other tanks worked up the east and west sides of the village.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] After confused fighting, Flers was in British hands by 10.30, and 12th ESR 'mopped up' the dugouts with bombs, sending large numbers of prisoners back.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Other Germans fled towards Gueudecourt, while their artillery put down a heavy bombardment on the village.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] This caused disorganisation, and by now most of the officers and warrant officers who had gone into action were casualties (only one 2nd Lieutenant and one CSM came out unwounded).
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The operation orders had been received late and briefings had been inadequate: the NCOs and ORs were unaware that they were supposed to advance to one final objective, a line of trenches beyond the village.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Part of C Company did attempt to get there, but could not hold it.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The position of the battalion was now critical: scattered parties were in and around the village, which was under intense artillery fire, and were cut off by a German barrage laid in their rear.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] *Dinnaken* had broken down while withdrawing to the rally point, but two tanks that had accompanied the New Zealand Division up the west side of Flers came out of cover in the village and broke up a German counter-attack.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 122nd Brigade gathered what troops it could, including 228th Field Company, Royal Engineers, who had been building strongpoints, and stabilised the situation so that 12th ESR and the rest of the brigade could be relieved by 123rd Bde beginning at 16.30.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] About this time a shell landed in the shell hole occupied by Battalion HQ and Lt-Col Walmisley-Dresser was wounded.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] A stretcher-bearer got him back to the casualty clearing station while the remnants of the battalion slipped back in small parties.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] At 19.15 they were sent back to the reserve trenches.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On the evening of 16 September the second-in-command, Maj H.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Blakeney came up from the transport lines at Fricourt with 6 officers and 60 ORs and took command of the battalion.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Lieutenant-Col Walmisley-Dresser died of his wounds on 17 September and is buried at Heilly Station Cemetery at Méricourt.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] In all the battalion lost 16 out of 17 officers who went into action (five being killed in addition to the CO) and 288 out of 638 ORs.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 12th ESR was relieved from the reserve trenches on 18 September and marched back to a camp near Albert, where Maj C.H.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Kitchin (15th Hants) took over temporary command.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The battalion remained in camp reorganising for the rest of the month, then on 3 October it marched up to Mametz Wood.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The following afternoon, leaving the transport, quartermasters' stores and most of B Company at the wood, 12th ESR moved up to 'Gird Trench' to relieve troops of the New Zealand Division, which had launched the Battle of the Transloy Ridges on 1 October.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The Gird Trench area was under heavy bombardment, particularly 'Factory Corner', and the battalion suffered unnecessary casualties when their assigned guides led them over open ground to the new positions.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 122nd and 124th Brigades continued the operation on 7 October.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 12th ESR fell back to 'Goose Alley' to be in brigade support with a section of 228th Fd Co.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Soon after Zero at 13.45 Goose Alley was heavily shelled, and it was not until 14.10 that 12th ESR was able to get forward to occupy the 'jumping off' trench from which 18th KRRC had launched its assault.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] At 16.30 122nd Bde ordered 12th ESR forward to reinforce 11th RWK, which had lost heavily, the battalion having to send patrols forward to find the remnants of the West Kents.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The East Surreys then moved up a sunken road under heavy shellfire to reach them without loss.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The battalion consolidated and held the ground that the West Kents had captured, digging communication trenches back to the old line after dark.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The working parties and covering patrols were called in at daybreak, but the whole of next day (8 October) was spent improving the trenches, with 30 per cent of the battalion positioned in 'Gird Support Trench' to prevent overcrowding.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Relief by 123rd Bde was delayed by heavy shelling before 12th ESR could withdraw to the reserve trench ('Switch Trench'), where reinforcements came up from the details at the transport lines.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The battalion left Mametz Wood on 11 October and went back by Decauville Railway to a rest camp at Ribemont, having lost 8 ORs killed, 1 officer and 47 ORs wounded, and 8 missing, without having made an attack.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] These men had found themselves turned into cyclists, and were now dismounted and rebadged as East Surreys.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] At the same time Lt-Col Lee returned to command the battalion.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 18 October 12th ESR began a series of slow train journeys north, finally marching into 'Ontario Camp' near Reningelst on 25 October, when 41st Division joined Second Army.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] There was much work to do in maintaining the trenches in the waterlogged ground, under German observation and shellfire from Messines Ridge, and battalions were relieved every five days, suffering a trickle of casualties on every tour of duty.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Drafts of replacements arrived each month: 50 from 2/5th East Surreys in December, 100 from 3rd East Surreys in January 1917 and 50 from 1st East Surreys in February.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 7 April 47th (2nd London) Division carried out a large raid, and 12th ESR was tasked with making a supporting demonstration in the St Eloi sector.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The artillery carried out an all-day bombardment, rising to a crescendo in the evening, and 12th ESR lit smoke candles and bombs, attracting retaliatory shellfire and the firing of a small German mine and suffering a few casualties.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] By April the enemy had identified 'Dead Dog Farm' as the HQ of the battalion in the line, and it came under increasing shellfire, especially on 11 and 12 April when 12th ESR was in the line.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] In early 1917 Second Army was preparing for the Battle of Messines.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The object of this attack was to capture the Wytschaete–Messines Ridge with its fine observation positions over the British line.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] In the weeks before the battle units were withdrawn for careful rehearsals behind the lines, and leaders down to platoon level were taken to see a large model of the ridge constructed at Scherpenberg.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 12th ESR left Ontario Camp on 25 April for the brigade training area several days' march away at Quemberghe.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] At the end of the training, which included forming up on tapes in the dark for pre-dawn attacks, 41st Division returned to the Dickebusch area, with 12th ESR in 'Micmac Camp' from 17 May, going into the St Eloi trenches again on 19 May.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Lieutenant-Col Lee gave up the command on health grounds and was succeeded on 22 May by Maj E.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Knapp (South African Defence Force) who came from 23rd Middlesex in 123rd Bde and was promoted to Lt-Col.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Under his command the Bermondsey Battalion, who were already called the 'Shiny Twelfth', gained the additional nickname of 'Knapp's Nippers'.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] A mass of heavy, medium and field artillery began systematic destruction of enemy strongpoints and batteries on 21 May and the bombardment became intense from 31 May.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The area to be attacked was obvious to the enemy; however the surprise element was the line of 19 great mines dug under the ridge.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] During the waiting period German retaliatory fire drove 12th ESR's transport out of Micmac camp and it had to shelter at 'Chippewa Camp'.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The rest of the battalion was employed in carrying up ammunition for a battery of 18-pounder field guns concealed in the reserve line at Dead Dog Farm.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] After the raid the battalion established a telephone post in No man's land ready for the attack.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On the night of 6/7 June 12th ESR left Chippewa Camp and moved up (D Company losing a few casualties to desultory shellfire on the congested road) to its concentration area in front of 'Old French Trench' by 01.30 to wait for Zero hour.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The mines were fired at 03.10 on 7 June.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] After the mines exploded and the barrage came down the battalions advanced under bright moonlight, although the visibility became bad because of the smoke and dust from the mine explosions and barrage.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 123rd Brigade's role was to capture the St Eloi salient by a converging attack as far as the 'Damstrasse', a raised driveway leading to a former chateau.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] From this first objective (the Blue Line) 122nd Bde was to take over and continue to 'Oblong Reserve Trench' as the second objective (the Black Line).
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The Blue Line was taken by 05.00 with hardly any resistance, and 122nd Bde moved off at 05.10 and formed up along the Damstrasse by 06.00, with 12th ESR on the right.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] At 06.30 the waves moved up close to the standing barrage, which began to creep forward by 50 yards (46 m) lifts at 06.50.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Pressing on close behind, the battalion cleared the enemy dugouts and trenches in 'Pheasant Wood' and 'Denys Wood', meeting little resistance and taking many prisoners.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Battalion HQ was established in a shell-hole in Pheasant Wood and between 0715 and 08.30 12th ESR consolidated a line of four advanced posts and an observation post in Denys Wood, although the enemy continued shelling the area.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] After a lengthy bombardment, the British guns reached a new crescendo at 15.10 and 24th Division passed through 41st Division 's lines to take the final objective, the 'Green Line', completing the task at 17.00.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The battalion's losses in the operation were 30 ORs killed, 6 officers and 153 ORs wounded and 6 missing, having taken 268 prisoners, 6 machine guns and 2 trench mortars.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] A number of medals were awarded to the battalion, including a Distinguished Service Order (DSO) for Lt-Col Knapp.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On the morning of 8 June the battalion went back to Old French Trench, where it was engaged in salvage work until 12 June, then went into support in 'Old Oak' and 'Old Oak Support' trenches with Battalion HQ in the ruins of 'White Chateau'.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] It remained in this sector alternating spells of duty with 20th DLI until 6 July when it was relieved and marched to La Roukloshille.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] There it rested and supplied working parties for 228th Fd Co.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Pennell of 18th KRRC took temporary command of 12th ESR during Lt-Col Knapp's absence on leave.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 23 July 41st Division returned to the line for the opening of the Flanders Offensive (the Third Battle of Ypres).
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 12th ESR went up on 24 July and took over the line between 'Ecluse Trench' and Old French Trench, with Battalion HQ at Lock House at the Spoil Bank by the Ypres–Comines Canal.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] After days of bombardment the offensive began on 31 July with the Battle of Pilckem Ridge.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Second Army had a minor role in covering the right flank of the main offensive by Fifth Army.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 41st Division made an attack on either side of the canal with limited objectives.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] At 16.30 Acting Lt-Col Pennell was ordered to take 12th ESR forward to complete the capture of the village.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] A composite company attacked at 18.15 and the coloured flare to indicate success was fired at 19.59.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 12th ESR established a line near 'Forret Farm' just beyond the village, having suffered only light casualties.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] It consolidated and occupied this line next day, establishing a company HQ and strongpoint in Forret Farm when it was found to be unoccupied.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The trenches were very wet, sometimes waist-deep, ration parties had difficulty getting through, and men started to suffer from Trench foot, most of C Company having to be evacuated.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 5 August a large party of specialist German stormtroopers succeeded in getting back into Hollebeke in the morning mist and Lt-Col Pennell led the Battalion HQ staff of observers, signallers and orderlies in a counter-attack.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] With a platoon of 15th Hants they retook the village and Forret Farm, finding that most of B and D Companies of 12th ESR had been surrounded and overrun.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] By noon the position was stabilised and a number of Germans had surrendered.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Only 90 men of the exhausted battalion came out when it was relieved, but others who had attached themselves to other units in the confusion came in later.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The battalion details at the transport lines formed a composite platoon to relieve them.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] In the six days in the line, 12th ESR had lost 30 killed or died of wounds, 115 wounded, 54 missing (mostly prisoners) and 125 sick.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Among the awards to the battalion, A/Lt-Col Pennell received a DSO.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The battalion went back into the line on 10 August, with a trench strength of 5 officers and 253 ORs.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] It was finally relieved on the night of 13/14 August and sent to Méteren for rest and reorganisation.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 20 August it moved by lorry to Zudausques, near St Omer, where 41st Division underwent training.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] When it returned to Ypres in mid-September reinforcements and returning sick had brought 12th ESR back up to 41 officers and 823 ORs, and Lt-Col Knapp had returned to lead the training.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Drafts had been received from several regiments, including 2/5th ESR, but these men had already been well trained in the specialisations (Lewis gunners, bombers and rifle grenadiers) required by the new 'fighting platoon' tactics, which the battalion practised over a 'shell-hole' training area.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The training emphasised rifle grenades for use against the number of enemy pillboxes now being encountered.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 14 September the battalion began marching by stages back to the Ypres Salient and on the night of 19/20 September 41st Division moved into its positions by the canal for the next attack up onto the 'Tower Hamlets' spur.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 122nd Brigade was on the left, with 12th ESR in the second line 50 yards (46 m) behind 18th KRRC, each battalion being on a two company frontage.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The right and left companies of 12th ESR were split by a marsh near 'Bodmin Copse', but they would be able to close up as they advanced.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The battalion sent a 'trench strength' of 18 officers and 447 ORs into action.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Although the Battle of the Menin Road Ridge is generally held to have been a great success, this was not 12th ESR's experience.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The battalion was late getting into position, the guides having got lost, and finally lined up on the tapes at 03.00.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The barrage began at 05.40 and paused for 3 minutes for the first wave to close up, then began creeping towards the first objective, with 12th ESR closely following 18th KRRC and reinforcing them when a pillbox held them up just beyond Bodmin Copse.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] After half an hour the enemy were dispersed with rifle grenades.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 12th ESR then crossed the shell-torn ground to the second objective (the Blue Line) about 07.30.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Here the battalion had to form a defensive flank to the right because 124th Bde were pinned down by the pillboxes at 'Tower Hamlets'.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The battalion was due to advance on the Green Line at 10.00, but only about 40 men were able to do so because of the fire from the right.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Similarly, 11th RWK on the left were hampered by this fire and also had to form a defensive flank and link up with 12th ESR.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The first signs of enemy counter-attacks were seen at 14.00, and by 16.00 they had retaken the Green Line and 12th ESR was fighting in isolated parties to hold the rest.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Lieutenant-Col Knapp had few men under his direct command and had already been slightly wounded while trying to deal with snipers.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] At 18.30, 123rd Bde came up from reserve and completed 124th Bde's tasks, allowing a party of 15th Hants and the remnants of 12th ESR to assault the final objective on the sur ahead.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] They then had to dig in and hold the ground under shell and machine gun fire until 01.00 on 23 September when fresh troops came up to take over, and the battalion could withdraw to Ridge Wood Camp.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] It had lost 9 officers and 33 ORs killed or mortally wounded, 5 officers and 197 ORs wounded, and 57 missing, roughly two-thirds of those who went into action.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Among the wounded was Lt-Col Knapp, who was wounded a second time the following day, this tine severely by a shell.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 41st Division was now sent to the Flanders Coast, with 12th ESR at La Panne, near Dunkirk, where it reorganised and trained.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 15 October it went into the coast defences at Oostduinkerke-Bad and later at Coudekerque-Branche, where it was under intermittent fire from long-range guns.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Large drafts were received from 2/5th and 2/6th ESR and other regiments, and by the end of October the battalion's strength had recovered to 40 officers and 864 ORs.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Puttick of the 11th RWK took temporary command when Lt-Col Knapp was evacuated, but on 16 October he went to command 15th Hants and was replaced by Acting Lt-Col C.F.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 7 November 1917 41st Division was informed that it was to be transferred to reinforce the Italian Front, and 12th ESR boarded two trains at Loon-Plage on 12 November.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The division completed its concentration in the Mantua area by 18 November.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 122nd Brigade then undertook a five-day march of 120 miles (190 km) to take up positions in the Montello sector.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The gruelling march was conducted in battle order with advanced guards and night outposts.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 1 December the brigade took over a sector of the front line along the River Piave, with 12th ESR and 11th RWK alternating between the reserve and front line positions along the face of the escarpment, in the snow and with occasional heavy shelling.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 24/25 December the battalion moved down to the river, where it occupied positions that included an island.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Working parties began constructing dugouts because of the frequent shelling.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The battalion now had two bands: an earlier fife and drum band was resuscitated, and a brass band was formed from men received as drafts from other ESR battalions.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] It adopted the Scottish ballad *The Lass O' Gowrie* as its regimental march (it had originally been used by the 70th Foot, later 2nd Bn East Surreys).
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 16–17 January 1918 the battalion marched to billets in Loria, where it remained training for a month before moving to Venegazzù in the Monte Grappa sector.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] While there the division received orders to return to the Western Front.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 12th ESR entrained at Carmignano on 1 March and reached Doullens in the Somme sector early on 5 March, going into billets at Halloy, where 41st Division was in GHQ Reserve.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The BEF was suffering a manpower crisis in early 1918, and each infantry brigade was reduced from four to three battalions, the surplus units being disbanded and drafted to provide reinforcements.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] When 41st Division arrived from Italy it conformed to the new organisation, and 11th RWK was disbanded from 122nd Bde.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 7th (S) Bn, East Surreys, in 12th (Eastern) Division, had been disbanded earlier, and now a large number of its men were posted to 12th ESR.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Lieutenant-Col Stallard left on 17 March and was replaced by Lt-Col G.L.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 41st Division was already preparing to reinforce Third Army (the battalion transport and equipment was sent forward on 20 March, 12th ESR's going to Achiet-le-Grand) when the long-anticipated German spring offensive began early on 21 March.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Soon Third Army was under intense pressure and 41st Division was ordered up.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] At 16.00 12th ESR entrained at Mondicourt for Pont-Remy station, but the trains were diverted to Achiet-le-Grand where the battalion detrained under shellfire, joined the transport, and marched to Savoy Camp near Bihucourt.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] At 06.00 next morning 41st Division was sent into IV Corps' Reserve area around Favreuil, with 124th Bde and part of 122nd Bde occupying the rear defence zone (the 'Green Line'), while 12th ESR formed a defensive flank facing north.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The battalion reached its position at 05.00 on 23 March and A and B Companies dug in overlooking the village of Mory, supported by C and D Companies remaining behind the crest.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Mory was the hinge between IV Corps and VI Corps and was under attack by the enemy.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 13th East Surreys (Wandsworth) of 40th Division recaptured Mory during the afternoon and held it until nightfall, but there was still a gap between the two battalions, so D Company was sent to extend A & B Companies' line and patrols went out to contact 13th ESR.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 12th ESR remained in position under shellfire throughout 24 March until 18.00, when the battalion was ordered to withdraw to a line in front of Sapignies (the Red Line) and hold it as long as it could while the rest of the brigade prepared new defences behind.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] This was done after dark, and it dug in on a forward slope behind Favreuil.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] At 03.30 next morning British troops retreated through the battalion's positions and an hour later it discovered that that both flanks of the battalion were open, while D Company had followed orders to fall back in conformity with the units to the right.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] At 05.30 Lt-Col Brown sent A & B Companies back to the Sapignies ridge, while he stayed with C Company and a few machine gunners.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] This rearguard held up enemy attacks for 5 hours, 'simply mowing down the enemy'.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Finally at 10.30, finding the enemy round both flanks, Brown gave the order to retire, but only he and one NCO got away over the open slope, the whole of C Company being captured.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] However, this stand had allowed the 15th Hants to dig a new line in front of Bihucourt, and for the Royal Artillery to get 60 guns away from Achiet-le-Grand (though much of 12th ESR's stores and records there had to be burned to prevent their capture).
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The rest of 12th ESR under Capt Walker held the Sapignies line until 13.00 when it withdrew to the Bihucourt line, where it made a stand and assisted a counter-attack by 15th Hants.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] At 01.00 on 26 March the battalion was ordered to pull back to Bucquoy, and it held a line near Gommecourt through a quiet day, although the rear areas were still being shelled.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] At 01.00 on 27 March it moved back to Bienvillers where the men rested in a field outside the village during another quiet day.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The Germans had been stopped at Bucquoy, the 'Great Retreat' was over, and next day the battalion returned to the line in support 124th Bde in front of Bucquoy.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] During the month 12th ESR had lost 2 officers and 19 ORs killed or died of wounds, 6 officers and 91 ORs wounded, 2 officers and 118 ORs prisoners, and another 51 missing; however, its strength was still 32 officers and 709 ORs.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Lieutenant-Col Brown was later warded the DSO for his work.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 41st Division was finally relieved on the night of 1/2 April after 10 days' fighting, and was taken by motor bus to a rest area.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] It then moved north by marching and train to rejoin Second Army at Ypres, which was now considered a quiet area.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 12th ESR rested at 'School Camp' at Poperinge where it received drafts of about 400 reinforcements, including men from 22nd Londons from Bermondsey and other battalions of the East Surreys.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On the night of 7/8 April the battalion took over the front line in the Passchendaele sector, at the head of the salient that had been captured during the Third Battle of Ypres.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] After four days under occasional shellfire 12th ESR was relieved.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The Germans had launched the second phase of their Spring offensive (the Battle of the Lys) just south of Ypres and made such rapid progress that by 13 April the position in the Passchendaele salient was critical.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 12th ESR was sent to dig a series of new lines and 'defended localities' in front of Ypres to which the frontline units retired.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The battalion then worked on the 'Green Line' defences further back for the rest of the month, suffering casualties from gas shells and long-range shelling.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] When not on working parties, or awaiting orders to counter-attack that never came, the men carried out rifle practice.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 2/3 May 12th ESR went back to begin spells in the new front line, which consisted of a chain of outposts.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Both side's artillery and aircraft remained active.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 4–5 June the battalion travelled by rail to Bayenghem in the Second Army Training Area where 41st Division underwent intensive training.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 27 June the battalion moved to Rubrouck when 41st Division went into reserve for XIV French Corps.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 1/2 July the battalion relieved a battalion of the 103rd French Infantry Regiment at La Clytte, where it began alternating with the other battalions of 122nd Bde in the front line.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] German artillery was fairly active against these positions and both sides carried out raids, leading to casualties.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 25 July a company of newly-arrived US Army troops was attached to the battalion for their introduction to front line duty.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 8 August, when the Allied Hundred Days Offensive began further south with the Battle of Amiens, 122nd Bde's front was particularly active: 12th ESR loaned C Company and a platoon of D Company to 15th Hants to support that battalion's night attack to straighten the brigade front.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 11 August the Germans carried out a strong counter-raid that was beaten off with Lewis guns.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Artillery fire and aggressive patrolling was carried out by both sides for the next week., and casualties were numerous.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 28 August 41st Division began to be relieved by 27th US Infantry Division and 12th ESR went by train to billets in Esquerdes, near St Omer.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] However, on the evening of 30 August the Germans were seen to be shelling their own line in front of 41st Division's positions, and patrols from 10th Queen's found that the enemy had retired.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 41st and 27th US Divisions immediately began following up, and 12th ESR was hurriedly recalled from its billets.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 106th US Infantry Regiment reached a line of trenches along the Vierstraat–Kemmel road, but got held up next morning (2 September), and that evening 12th ESR was ordered to take over at Vierstraat crossroads.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Although Lt-Col Brown was told that the enemy had been cleared out, patrols that night ran into strong enemy parties, and next morning the battalion found isolated pockets of both Germans and inexperienced Americans.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] In addition to this botched relief, Battalion HQ was badly shelled with gas during the afternoon.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 122nd Brigade was ordered to make a formal advance on the following day.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] During the night A and B Companies had to fight their way to their jumping off position along 'Chinese Trench' astride the Vierstraat–Wytschaete road and suffered serious casualties, but C and D Companies were able to pass through and get in position by 04.00.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The barrage came down at 05.30 on 4 September and the two companies jumped off before the enemy counter-barrage came down.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] By 06.15 they had reached their objective at the west edge of Bois Quarante, but D Company had suffered heavy casualties from the flank, where 15th Hants had been held up.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] A and B Companies went forwards again to reinforce them and form a defensive flank.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] It emerged that the enemy were holding the dominating Wytschaete Ridge in strength, and by 13.00 12th ESR's casualties were so serious (all but one company commander had been hit) that it had to withdraw to the Vierstraate Switch line.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] There it formed a single composite company that remained under heavy shellfire all day.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On the night of 5/6 September the battalion was relieved and went into divisional reserve at Hoograaf Farm.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] In what for most of Second Army had been a simple pursuit, 12th ESR had lost 3 officers and 42 ORs killed, 11 officers and 180 ORs wounded or gassed, and 7 missing.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] It carried out another spell of duty in the Vierstraate line from 17/18 to 21/22 September, spending the rest of the month training, with special emphasis on dealing with strongpoints and machine gun nests.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The Allies launched a coordinated series of offensives on 26–29 September.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Second Army's attack (the Fifth Battle of Ypres) began on 28 September: there was little resistance.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 12th ESR joined in the pursuit next day with D Company as advance guard.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The battalion crossed the Ypres–Comines Canal and encountered a strongpoint near Kortewilde which it dealt with.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 30 September it moved forward again with A Company in the lead and made contact with 35th Division on the left.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 1 October the battalion was 41st Division's advance guard, moving towards Menin, but when the mist cleared it was held up by a strong line of machine gun posts at Geluwe, and casualties were heavy.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Weston of 122nd Bde came up and joined the battalion but then disappeared.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 122nd Brigade HQ reported him 'Missing, believed killed' and Divisional HQ ordered Lt-Col Brown to take temporary command of the brigade.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] About noon next day Brig-Gen Weston reappeared, having cleared some of the machine gun positions with a party of 12th ESR and remained there overnight: they were now waiting for the rest of the battalion to catch up.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The rest of 122nd Bde passed through and continued the attack, with a company of 12th ESR mopping up Geluwe.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The brigade held off a counter-attack in the evening.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 3 October the battalion was relieved in the advance, but remained as support battalion to 124th Bde until 6 October when it went back to Ypres to clean up and train.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Its casualties during the week had been 17 ORs killed, 7 officers and 81 ORs wounded and 9 ORs missing.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] After a few days in camp at Abeele, 12th ESR went by train to 'Clapham Junction' on the Menin Road on 12 October and marched back to Geluwe to prepare for the next attack (the Battle of Courtrai).
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The barrage opened at 05.32 on 14 October and 122nd Bde attacked with 12th ESR in the centre.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Advancing through the fog and smokescreen on a two-company frontage the battalion reached the Blue Line objective at 07.45 and pushed on to reach the Red Line at 08.30, followed closely by the two support companies.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] It had quickly overrun a number of pillboxes and machine gun posts, but casualties were relatively light (2 officer and 14 ORs killed, 1 officer and 61 ORs wounded).
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 122nd Brigade remained in support next day, then marched several miles east on 16 October to stay in support for 123rd Bde as the pursuit accelerated and the first liberated Belgian civilians began to be seen.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 12th ESR remained at Gulleghem under intermittent shelling until 19 October, when it crossed the River Lys to the outskirts of Courtrai, moving in to the liberated town the following day.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 41st Division attacked again on 21 October to close up to the River Scheldt east of the Courtrai-Le Bossuyt Canal, a 9,000 yards (8,200 m) advance for 122nd Bde.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The attack began at 07.00 and 15th Hants and 18th KRRC successfully crossed the canal, but 12th ESR (C & D Companies leading) ran into belts of wire and machine gun fire after advancing about 2 miles (3.2 km).
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The action continued next day, when the battalion got three companies across the canal near Knokke, but they were then held up by enfilade fire before they had reached their forming-up position.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] This fire came from a tunnel where the railway crossed the canal which had been strongly wired and was held by a machine gun battalion.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] This strongpoint had held up 124th Bde's advance the day before, and now C Company suffered heavy casualties before it succeeded in forcing the position with the assistance of 124th Bde.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 122nd Brigade was then rested until 26 October, when 12th ESR and 18th KRRC prepared to assault Avelgem on the Scheldt.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] However, just before Zero civilians reported the town abandoned, which was confirmed by patrols from 12th ESR, who secured the bridgehead and established posts on the far bank.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The battalion went back to Knokke next day.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Its casualties from 14 to 26 October amounted to 3 officers and 33 ORs killed, 7 officers and 167 ORs wounded, and 30 ORs missing.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] It suffered a few more from shelling and night bombing over the next few days, but it had made its last attack.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 8 November it carried out a dress rehearsal on the Lys for a proposed night assault crossing of the Scheldt, but this became unnecessary when the enemy retreated.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 12th ESR crossed the river on 10 November and was at Etikhove near Oudenaarde when the Armistice with Germany came into force next day.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 12 November 41st Division learned that it had been selected as one of the British divisions to form part of the occupation forces in Germany.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 12th ESR was billeted at Everbeek until lines of communication had been established.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] It resumed its march on 12 December, resting at Waterloo on the way.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] It spent Christmas and New Year at Warnant-Dreye.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 7 January 1919 the battalion entrained at Huy for the last part of its journey into Germany, crossing the Rhine by the Hohenzollern Bridge at Cologne and taking over the outpost line at Marialinden east of the city.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Demobilisation got under way in January.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] On 15 March 41st Division was redesignated 'London Division', and 9th East Surreys from 24th Division was transferred in to replace 12th East Surreys.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Nine officers and 300 ORs from 12th ESR transferred to 9th ESR; many of these men had been 'called up' in 1918 and would have longer to wait for their demobilisation, others had signed on for an additional year with the British Army of the Rhine.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The remainder of the battalion was billeted at the Kaiserin Krankenhaus hospital in Cologne to await demobilisation.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] By 22 May the battalion had been reduced to a cadre of 4 officers and 36 ORs, who were transferred to Antwerp, from where they sailed to England, arriving at Aldershot on 28 May.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] They was entertained to lunch by the Mayor of Bermondsey on 31 May and finally disbanded at Aldershot 10 June 1919.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] In addition, all ranks wore a green cloth disc on each arm.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The battalion's 'bombers' also wore a red grenade badge on their sleeves.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] At Messines the battalion used the image of a dagger (its codename) on battlefield signboards.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] 41st Division's sign was a white diagonal stripe across a coloured square, which was green in the case of 122nd Brigade.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] This was not worn on the uniform but only on vehicles and signboards.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] Battalion transport vehicles carried a numeral on a background of brigade colour; as the senior battalion in the brigade, 12th ESR's numeral would have been '1'.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] War-raised battalions that served overseas were granted a King's Colour at the end of the war, and 12th ESR received its on 12 February 1919 while on the Rhine.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The Regular and Territorial battalions later had embroidered on their King's Colours 10 selected Battle honours (from the many they were awarded after World War I) instead of them being added to those traditionally borne on the Regimental Colour.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The Service Battalions were disbanded and laid up their colours before the battle honours were awarded.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] However, it is reported that the King's Colour of 12th ESR had 12 (not 10) honours added to it when it was in the keeping of the Brough of Bermondsey.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] However, the colour was later found in a council storeroom and was then handed over to the Old Comrades' Association, who with WO permission laid it up in St Mary's Church, Rotherhithe in 1933.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The Bermondsey & Rotherhithe war memorial at Mill Pond Bridge off Jamaica Road includes the borough coat of arms worn as a collar badge by the men of 12th ESR.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The 41st Division memorial is at Flers, the bronze figure by Albert Toft being a copy of his Royal Fusiliers War Memorial in London.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] It was erected in 1923 but was not officially unveiled.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The pedestal lists all of the division's units, but a party from 12th East Surreys on pilgrimage to the battlefields found that their battalion was wrongly listed as the '10th'.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] This inscription was rectified by the time the monument was officially unveiled at a ceremony in 1932.
[src:bermondsey/12th-service-battalion-east-surrey-regiment-bermondsey-p02] The East Surrey Regiment's memorial chapel is in All Saints Church, Kingston upon Thames.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] On 24 February 1983, a by-election was held in the Bermondsey constituency in South London, following the resignation of Bob Mellish.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] Peter Tatchell stood as the candidate for the Labour Party, and Simon Hughes stood for the Liberal Party.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] Following a bitter campaign, the Liberals made huge gains and took the seat, with a majority of votes cast.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] Labour's vote fell from 63.6 per cent in May 1979 to 26.1 per cent as Tatchell came a distant second, while the Conservative candidate, Robert Hughes, managed only fourth place, losing his deposit.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] With a swing of 44.2%, the 1983 Bermondsey by-election is the second-largest by-election swing in British political history.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] Bob Mellish had represented the constituency and its predecessors in the House of Commons since 1946.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] He was the Labour Chief Whip from 1969 until 1976, but had become disenchanted with the left-wing drift of the Labour Party.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] He resigned from the party in August and his Parliamentary seat in November 1982, amid much acrimony within the party.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] He had been in dispute with his constituency party for several years and had earlier threatened to resign if Peter Tatchell was selected as the next prospective parliamentary candidate.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] He was recruited by the Conservative government to the board of the London Docklands Development Corporation; as he did not wish to be disqualified, the post was made non-salaried until such time as Mellish chose to accept payment.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] This meant that Mellish had a paid job to go to as soon as he wanted.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] On 7 November 1981, Bermondsey Labour Party selected Peter Tatchell, its secretary, as prospective Parliamentary candidate.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] Tatchell was a leading member of the left-wing faction that had taken control of the local party the previous year.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] This call to civil disobedience was considered a call to violent action by some, and was used "as a stick to beat [Tatchell] with" by political opponents.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] For example, the article came to the attention of James Wellbeloved, a former London Labour MP who had defected to the Social Democratic Party; Wellbeloved then referred to it in a Parliamentary Question to Margaret Thatcher on 3 December.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] Labour Party leader Michael Foot responded to Wellbeloved by denouncing Tatchell's article and declared "the individual concerned is not an endorsed member of the Labour Party and as far as I'm concerned never will be".
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] As to whether Tatchell was a member of the Labour Party itself, Foot later clarified that he meant to say "endorsed candidate" instead of "endorsed member" in his response to Wellbeloved.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] At the next meeting of the Labour Party National Executive Committee, Tatchell was narrowly rejected as a candidate.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] Mellish was not reassured about the future direction of the Labour Party and resigned from it on 2 August 1982, a clear preliminary to resigning his seat, which he did by taking the Chiltern Hundreds on 1 November that year.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] The left wing of the Labour Party agreed Tatchell would be eligible for selection, and Tatchell was duly selected again in January 1983.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] Tabloid newspapers had begun researching his background when Foot denounced him, in particular Tatchell's activities with the Gay Liberation Front in the early 1970s.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] Several stories were published which made it clear that he was gay.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] At the 1981 Greater London Council election, the Liberal Party had come second in Bermondsey.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] They chose their GLC candidate Simon Hughes, a barrister who had moved to the constituency earlier that year, to fight the by-election.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] The Conservatives chose Robert Hughes (no relation), who was a Greater London Council (GLC) councillor for Croydon Central.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] Among those who applied for the Conservative nomination but were not chosen was Sara Keays, then having an as yet unrevealed affair with Cecil Parkinson.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] The right-wing former Labour leader of Southwark Borough Council, John O'Grady, who had been a target for the left-wing faction locally, also decided to stand under the banner 'Real Bermondsey Labour' with Bob Mellish's support and encouragement.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] His campaign was dominated by personal opposition to Tatchell and defence of his leadership of the council.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] Twelve other candidates stood, including Screaming Lord Sutch, appearing for the first time under the Official Monster Raving Loony Party label, and the Dowager Lady Birdwood.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] Esmond Bevan intended to stand as an independent Labour candidate, but erroneously entered his occupation in the section on the nomination papers headed 'description', thus appearing on ballot papers as "Systems Designer".
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] The Labour campaign started disastrously when it was discovered that the first leaflets had been printed at Cambridge Heath Press, owned by the Militant tendency (then practising entryism in the Labour Party; a group whose five key members were expelled two days before polling day).
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] The leaflets were all pulped and reprinted, but the cost of the first printing still counted against the limit for election spending.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] There was much controversy over Tatchell's homosexuality.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] The Labour Party persuaded Tatchell to keep quiet about his sexual orientation, although he had previously declared himself 'out'.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] Various campaigners for opposition candidates, as well as many within the Labour Party, made homophobic comments about Tatchell.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] Widespread graffiti throughout the constituency referred to him in derogatory terms, while some of those putting up posters in his support found their windows attacked.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] Tatchell received hate mail, including a live cartridge, and was attacked when out in the street.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] On the last weekend of the campaign, an anonymous leaflet was sent round the constituency headed "Which Queen will you vote for?", contrasting the republican Tatchell, who was pictured looking very effeminate, with Queen Elizabeth II.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] The leaflet gave Tatchell's home address and telephone number.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] An alternative analysis of Tatchell's eventual defeat was given by David Sutch, the Official Monster Raving Loony Party candidate, in his 1991 autobiography.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] When being interviewed on TV at the by-election count, Sutch related to Tatchell how horrified he was at the treatment Tatchell had received, but added that "what I did not tell him was that he had been so bad a candidate that he had largely brought it on himself".
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] Sutch criticised Tatchell's preference for press conferences and press releases rather than traditional meeting-and-greeting, which was generally regarded as the best way to win hearts and minds at a by-election.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] In a later interview, when the subject of Bermondsey came up, Sutch said that Tatchell "seemed to think all he needed to do to become the MP was turn up at the count".
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] During the by-election, members of the Liberal Party were accused of having joined in homophobic attacks on Tatchell.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] Male Liberal canvassers were seen wearing badges reading "I've been kissed by Peter Tatchell", although this seems to have been a poor taste joke by gay members of the Liberal Party.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] While this was criticised by Roy Hattersley at a news conference, elements of the Labour party were also hostile to Tatchell on the grounds both of his politics and his sexuality.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] In an interview with Simon Edge of *The Independent* published on 17 December 1996, the former Liberal Party Chief Executive, Andy Ellis, was asked whether he approved of the activity undertaken by the Liberal Gay Action Group, and replied "Nothing went on in Bermondsey that we were unhappy with".
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] Where there were things that were inappropriate or wrong, I apologise for that." Tatchell, by then a member of the Green Party, said that he had forgiven Hughes, saying "Simon benefited from these dirty tricks, but that was 23 years ago—I don't hold a grudge.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] It's time to forgive and move on", adding that Hughes should be judged on his 23-year record as an MP.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] Bermondsey was one of the first by-elections to be extensively polled.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] The polls showed, at first, that the Labour vote was substantially down on the 1979 election figures, but that none of the rival candidates were particularly close.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] As the campaign went on, the Liberal candidate began to move into a clear second position and the other candidates faded.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] Later in the campaign, there were rumours which claimed that the right wing of the Labour Party nationally wished to lose the seat, as it would prove that left-wing Labour candidates were unelectable.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] By the eve of poll, it was clear that large numbers of previously Labour voters were defecting to other parties, and that non-Labour voters were lining up in support of the Liberal candidate as the one most likely to beat Labour.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] The Liberals made huge gains and took the seat, with a majority of votes cast.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] Labour's vote fell from 63.6 per cent in May 1979 to 26.1 per cent as Tatchell came a distant second, while O'Grady took third.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] The Conservatives managed only fourth place, for the first time since the 1974 Newham South by-election, and the last in Britain until the 1991 Liverpool Walton by-election.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] All candidates other than Liberal and Labour lost their deposits.
[src:bermondsey/1983-bermondsey-by-election] Hughes would go on to represent Bermondsey and successor constituencies for the next 32 years, making him one of very few examples of MPs who took a formerly safe seat from another party and managed to hold it for a long period of time.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] The **22nd (County of London) Battalion, London Regiment (The Queen's)** was an auxiliary unit of the British Army.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] Formed in 1908 from Volunteer units in the Surrey suburbs of London that dated back to 1860, it was part of the London Regiment in the Territorial Force (TF).
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] Its battalions served on the Western Front and in Palestine during World War I.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] When the London Regiment was abolished in 1937 the unit reverted to the Queen's Royal Regiment (West Surrey) and during World War II its battalions fought in North Africa, Tunisia, Italy and North West Europe.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] It was amalgamated with other battalions into the Queen's Regiment in 1961.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] The invasion scare of 1859 led to the creation of the Volunteer Force and huge enthusiasm for joining Rifle Volunteer Corps (RVCs) composed of part-time soldiers eager to supplement the Regular British Army in time of need.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] These two units were attached for administrative purposes to the larger 19th (Lambeth) Surrey RVC, but on 10 October 1868 they were grouped into the 4th Administrative Battalion with its headquarters (HQ) at Bermondsey, moving to Rotherhithe the following year.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] Captain-Commandant James Payne of the 23rd was appointed Lieutenant-Colonel of the battalion.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] Samuel Bourne Bevington, a member of a leading Bermondsey industrial family, had enlisted as a Private in the 1st Surrey Rifles in 1859.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] He was appointed Captain-Commandant of the 10th Surrey RVC on 22 February 1868 and promoted to Major of the 4th Admin Bn under Payne's command on 17 December 1873.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] Payne remained commanding officer (CO) until 26 July 1884, when Bevington was promoted to succeed him.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] Bevington was CO of the battalion from until 1899 and later became the first mayor of the new Metropolitan Borough of Bermondsey.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] Volunteer corps were consolidated into larger units in 1880, when the 4th Surrey Admin Battalion became the **6th Surrey RVC**.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] The Childers Reforms of 1881 took Cardwell's reforms further, and the Volunteers were formally affiliated to their local Regular regiment, the 6th Surrey RVC becoming the **3rd Volunteer Battalion, Queen's Royal Regiment (West Surrey)** in March 1883.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] Battalion HQ moved back to Bermondsey in 1884.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] A Cadet Corps existed at Bermondsey from 1885 until 1895, and another was formed at Streatham Grammar School in 1899.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] While the sub-districts were later referred to as 'brigades', they were purely administrative organisations and the Volunteers were excluded from the 'mobilisation' part of the Cardwell system.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] The Stanhope Memorandum of December 1888 proposed a more comprehensive Mobilisation Scheme for Volunteer units, which would assemble in their own brigades at key points in case of war.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] In peacetime these brigades provided a structure for collective training.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] Under this scheme the Volunteer Battalions of the Queen's and the East Surrey Regiment formed the Surrey Brigade.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] The assembly point for the brigade was at Caterham Barracks, the Brigade of Guards' depot conveniently situated for the London Defence Positions along the North Downs.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] After Black Week in December 1899, the Volunteers were invited to send active service units to assist the Regulars in the Second Boer War.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] The War Office decided that one company 116 strong could be recruited from the volunteer battalions of any infantry regiment that had a regular battalion serving in South Africa.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] The Queen's VBs accordingly raised a service company, which was replaced by a second after a year's service.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] The 3rd VB contributed a section of men to each company, and to the City Imperial Volunteers (CIVs).
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] This service earned the 3rd VB its first Battle honour: **South Africa 1900–02**.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] In the reorganisation after the end of the Boer War in 1902, the Surrey Brigade was split into separate East and West Surrey Brigades, under command of the respective regimental districts.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] Under the Haldane Reforms of 1908 the Volunteers were subsumed into the new Territorial Force (TF), administered by county Territorial Associations.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] Consequently, the 3rd VB Queen's became **22nd (County of London) Bn, London Regiment (The Queen's)**.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] It drill hall was at 2 Jamaica Road in Bermondsey.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] The four former Surrey battalions of the London Regiment (now 21st–24th Londons) comprised the 6th London Brigade in the TF's 2nd London Division.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] During World War I the 22nd Londons formed three battalions, of which the 1/22nd served on the Western Front and the 2/22nd served at Salonika and in Palestine.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] The London Regiment was abolished in 1938, and the battalion returned to the Queen's Royal Regiment (West Surrey) in 1937, now as that regiment's **6th (Bermondsey) Battalion**.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] Once again the unit formed two battalions, both of which served in the Battle of France, North Africa and in Italy.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] The 1/6th Queen's then served in North West Europe.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] Reformed postwar, the 6th (Bermondsey) Bn was amalgamated with other Territorial Army battalions to form the **3rd Battalion Queen's Royal Surrey Regiment** in 1961.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] The uniform of the 6th Surrey RVC was scarlet with blue facings, the same as the Queen's Regiment.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] The battalion later adopted the Paschal Lamb badge of the Queen's Regiment, which it retained as a battalion of the London Regiment.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] On conversion to the TF the battalion adopted the full dress of the Queen's (scarlet with blue facings), but khaki service dress was worn on most occasions.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] The Boer War memorial plaque inside St James's Church, Bermondsey, records the men of Bermondsey who volunteered for service in South Africa, including those of the 3rd VB, Queen's, who went out with the CIVs and the 1st and 2nd Service Sections.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] The 22nd Bn London Regiment is listed on the City and County of London Troops Memorial in front of the Royal Exchange, with architectural design by Sir Aston Webb and sculpture by Alfred Drury.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] The right-hand (southern) bronze figure flanking this memorial depicts an infantryman representative of the various London infantry units.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] Unveiled in 1921, the battalion's own World War I memorial on Old Jamaica Road in Bermondsey was Grade II listed in 2010.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] The World War II names were added when the worn lettering was re-cut in 1993.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] There is a statue to Samuel Bevington on Tooley Street at the south end of Tower Bridge.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] He is depicted in his mayoral robes, but the inscription on the stone plinth begins by recording his colonelcy of the 3rd VB, Queen's.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] The Regimental Colours presented to the 22nd Londons at Windsor Castle on 19 June 1909 are laid up in St Mary Magdalen Church, Bermondsey.
[src:bermondsey/22nd-county-of-london-battalion-london-regiment-the-queen-s] The King's Colour presented to the 2/22nd Bn at Horse Guards Parade on 26 February 1921 is held by the Surrey Infantry Museum.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The **56th (London) Infantry Division** was a Territorial Army infantry division of the British Army, which served under several different titles and designations.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The division served in the trenches of the Western Front during the First World War.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] Demobilised after the war, the division was reformed in 1920 and saw active service again in the Second World War in Tunisia and Italy.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The division was again disbanded in 1946 and reformed first as an armoured formation and then as an infantry division before final disbandment in 1961.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The Territorial Force (TF) was formed on 1 April 1908 following the enactment of the Territorial and Reserve Forces Act 1907 (7 Edw.7, c.9) which combined and re-organised the old Volunteer Force, the Honourable Artillery Company and the Yeomanry.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] On formation, the TF contained 14 infantry divisions and 14 mounted yeomanry brigades.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] One of the divisions was the **1st London Division**.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] It was a wholly new formation, although its three infantry brigade headquarters (HQs) had previously existed in the Volunteers, as had most of its constituent units.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The division comprised the first 12 battalions of the all-TF London Regiment, the first four London brigades of the Royal Field Artillery and the former Tower Hamlets Engineers; most of the supporting arms were newly raised.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] Essentially, all these units were based in inner London, while the 2nd London Division consisted of TF units recruited from suburban London.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] 1st London Division's HQ was at Friar's House in New Broad Street in the City of London.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] On the outbreak of war in August 1914 the division's units had just left for their annual training camps, the 1st and 3rd London brigades around Wool, Dorset, and the 2nd at Eastbourne, Sussex.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] They immediately returned to their drill halls to mobilise, and then proceeded to their initial war stations guarding railways in Southern England.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] 1/1st London Division immediately began supplying reinforcements to the Regular Army overseas.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] On 1 September the whole of 1/1st London Brigade, with its associated signal and medical units, set off to relieve the regular garrison of Malta; individual battalions joined the British Expeditionary Force (BEF) on the Western Front.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] By early January 1915 the 1st Line division had ceased to exist and its remaining units had been attached to its 2nd Line duplicate, the 2/1st London Division.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] On 7 January 1916 the Army Council authorised the re-formation in France of the division as **56th (1/1st London) Division**.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] As many as possible of the original units or other London units were assembled and by 21 February the bulk of the division had concentrated around Hallencourt between Abbeville and Arras under the command of Major General C.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] Amyatt Hull, an experienced officer who had until recently commanded an infantry brigade.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] Although the division was effectively a new formation, its constituent units were now experienced in trench warfare.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] After shaking down it took its place in the line in the Hébuterne sector.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The 56th Division's first operation as a complete formation was the attack on the Gommecourt Salient on 1 July 1916, the first day on the Somme.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] Extensive (and obvious) preparations were made for this attack, which was a diversion from the main Somme Offensive.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The leading battalions gained a lodgement in the German front line with comparatively light losses, but they came under heavy counter-attack and were cut off from reinforcements and ammunition resupply by an intense barrage laid down in no man's land by the German artillery.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] At nightfall the survivors made their way back to British lines, the division having lost over 4,300 casualties, mainly among the seven attacking battalions.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] By midnight on 10 November the division was relieved in the front line and drawn back into corps support, but the divisional artillery remained in action until the Cease Fire sounded at 11.00 on 11 November when the armistice of 11 November 1918 came into force.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] Its total casualties were 1,470 officers and 33,339 other ranks, killed, wounded and missing.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] After the armistice the division was engaged in road-mending *etc*.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The first parties left for demobilisation in mid-December and the division gradually dwindled.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] Divisional headquarters left for England on 18 May 1919 and the final cadre followed on 10 June.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The division began reforming in London District in April 1920.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The division reformed as the **56th (1st London) Infantry Division** in the renamed Territorial Army (TA) with much the same composition as before the First World War.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] In 1935 the increasing need for anti-aircraft (AA) defence, particularly for London, was addressed by converting the 47th (2nd London) Division into the 1st Anti-Aircraft Division.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] A number of London infantry battalions and were also converted to the AA role.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The remainder were concentrated in 56th (1st London) Division, which henceforth was simply designated **The London Division**, with its HQ at Finsbury Barracks.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] It was converted into a two-brigade motorised division in 1938 as **1st (London) Motor Division**, under Major-General Claude Liardet, the first TA officer appointed to command a division.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] After the Munich Crisis the TA once again expanded by creating duplicate units, and the 2nd (London) Motor Division began to come ito existence in March 1939.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] 1st (London) Motor Division mobilised at the outbreak of the Second World War in September 1939.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] It was reorganised as an infantry division in June 1940 and renamed the **56th (London) Infantry Division** on 18 November 1940.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The divisional insignia during the Second World War was changed to an outline of a black cat in a red background.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The cat stood for Dick Whittington's cat, a symbol of London.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The division remained in the United Kingdom during the Battle of France, moving to the Middle East in November 1942, where it served in Iraq and Palestine, until moving to Egypt in March 1943 and thence forward to Libya and the front, in April.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] This involved the division, commanded by Major-General Eric Miles, travelling some 2,300 miles (3,700 km) by road, a notable achievement and testament to the organization of the division and the ability of its mechanics and technicians.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The division, minus the 168th Brigade, fought in the final stages of the Tunisian Campaign, where it suffered heavy casualties facing the German 90th Light Infantry Division, including its GOC, Major-General Miles, who had been in command since October 1941.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] He was replaced by Major-General Douglas Graham.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The division sat out the Allied invasion of Sicily and moved to Italy in September 1943, where they fought in the landings at Salerno under the command of the British X Corps.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] During this time the 201st Guards Brigade joined the division, to replace the 168th Brigade which returned to the division in October, although the 201st remained attached until January 1944.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The 56th Division then crossed the Volturno Line in October and took part in the fighting around the Bernhardt Line.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] In January 1944, the 56th Division, now commanded by Major-General Gerald Templer, saw service in the Battle of Monte Cassino, serving there until February 1944 and participated in the Anzio campaign until relieved in March.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] After being withdrawn to Egypt at the end of March, the division, under Major-General John Whitfield, returned to Italy in July 1944, where it took part in the Battles along the Gothic Line and remained there until after Victory in Europe Day.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] During the fighting of 1944 and 1945, some of the infantry battalions that suffered heavy casualties were disbanded, to make up for an acute manpower shortage.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The division also took part in Operation Grapeshot, the Allied offensive which ended the war in Italy.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] After crossing the Volturno in October 1943, the division entered the town of Calvi Vecchia.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] Their attempts to radio the Fifth Army to cancel a planned bombing on the town failed.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] As a last resort, the 56th released an American homing pigeon, named G.I.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] Joe, which carried a message that reached the allies just as the planes were being warmed up.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The attack was called off and the town was saved from the planned air assault.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] In 1946, the 56th Division was demobilised then re-constituted in 1947 as the 56th (London) Armoured Division.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] On 20 December 1955, the Secretary of State for War informed the House of Commons that the armoured divisions and the 'mixed' division were to be converted to infantry.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The 56th Division was one of the eight divisions placed on a lower establishment for home defence only.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The territorial units of the Royal Armoured Corps were reduced to nine armoured regiments and eleven reconnaissance regiments by amalgamating pairs of regiments and the conversion of four RAC units to infantry.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] On 20 July 1960, a further reduction of the T.A. was announced in the House of Commons.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The Territorials were to be reduced from 266 fighting units to 195.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The reductions were carried out in 1961, mainly by the amalgamation of units.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] On 1 May 1961, the T.A. divisional headquarters were merged with regular army districts and matched with Civil Defence Regions, to aid the mobilisation for war.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The division ceased to exist as an independent entity and was linked to London District.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] The 4th Battalion, Queen's Royal Surrey Regiment was formed in 1961, by the amalgamation of the 6th Battalion, East Surrey Regiment and the 23rd London Regiment, with a Battalion HQ and HQ Company at Kingston upon Thames.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] It formed part of 47th (London) Infantry Brigade (56th London Division/District).
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] An echo of the 56th Division emerged again from 1987 to 1993, when the public duties battalions in the London District were grouped as the 56th Infantry Brigade.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] During the First World War, 56th (1/1st London) Division wore as its formation sign the sword symbolising the martyrdom of Paul the Apostle from the coat of arms of the City of London.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] A new sign consisting of the red sword of St Paul on a khaki background was authorised in 1936 for the London Division in case of war, but it was never used.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] During the Second World War, 56th (London) Division adopted a black silhouette of Dick Whittington's cat on a red ground as its formation sign, leading to its nickname of the 'Black Cats'.
[src:bermondsey/56th-london-division] From 1948 56th (London) Armoured Division wore a blue knight's helmet superimposed on the upright red sword, but in 1951 it resumed the black cat, now with the red sword superimposed.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The **7th Armoured Division (Desert Rats)** was an armoured division of the British Army.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] It was formed as the **Mobile Division (Egypt)** on 27 September 1938, after increased tensions between Britain and the Axis powers.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] This was part of an effort to reinforce and maintain the British strategic presence in Egypt to defend the Suez Canal, which was seen as vital to the British Empire's interests.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] In February 1940, the formation was renamed as the 7th Armoured Division.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] During its early years, the jerboa was adopted as the mascot and divisional insignia giving rise to the nickname Desert Rats.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The division fought in most of the major battles of the Western Desert campaign, was then engaged in the Tunisian campaign, and this was followed by the participation in the Italian campaign.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] It was then withdrawn from Italy and dispatched to the United Kingdom, to prepare for Operation Overlord.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] In June 1944, it landed in France and subsequently fought across western Europe and ended the war in Kiel and Hamburg, Germany.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] After the war it formed part of the British Army of the Rhine until it was disbanded in the 1950s.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The division's history and insignia was carried on by the 7th Armoured Brigade, until the brigade was disbanded in 2014, and is now maintained by the 7th Light Mechanised Brigade.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The Suez Canal, located in Egypt, was seen as a vital thoroughfare of the British Empire linking Britain with its colonial possessions in the east, especially British India.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] In addition, it held economic and prestigious importance.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] To maintain this, Egypt was occupied in 1882 and a protectorate was subsequently established.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] During the First World War, the Ottoman Empire came into conflict with the Entente, and the British presence in Egypt was reinforced.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Following the conclusion of hostilities and the British victory in the Middle Eastern theatre, Britain intended to maintain a garrison to protect the canal.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] However, military commitments had to be balanced with economic and geopolitical conditions.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] From a peak of 400,000 men in 1919, the garrison was reduced to 20,000 by 1921 and included the Cairo Cavalry Brigade.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] During the inter-war period, the Middle East and the canal gained further importance as oil production expanded, in addition to the development of aerial links between Britain and British India.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] In 1935, British policy shifted to view Italy as the principal threat towards British interests in the Middle East, following the Italian military build-up and invasion of Ethiopia.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] This crisis prompted the deployment an ad hoc formation called the Mobile Force, based around the Cairo Cavalry Brigade, to Mersa Matruh in the Western Desert, 170 mi (270 km) west of Alexandria.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Due to rain and sandstorms, vehicles became stuck or were stricken by mechanical issues resulting in the moniker "Mobile Farce" being applied.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The crisis also saw the UK and Egypt negotiate the Anglo-Egyptian treaty of 1936, which stated that the majority of the British military were to be confined to the canal zone except in emergencies.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] In the case of the latter, troops could be deployed across Egypt.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] This saw the increased importance of Mersa Matruh, as it became the location from which the defense of Egypt would be conducted if Italy attacked.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] A joint declaration on 2 January 1937, by Italy and Britain, to maintain the status quo around the Mediterranean, momentarily eased the situation between both countries.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] However, tensions quickly mounted and in early 1938 the garrison in Egypt was authorised to be brought up from its peace time to its wartime establishment.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] It was envisioned that behind the Mersa Matruh position, a force of one mobile and two infantry divisions could be assembled in the event of war.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] During the same year, the political situation in Europe escalated as Germany annexed Austria and then focused its attention on the German-dominated territory within Czechoslovakia.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] As Italy was closely aligned with Germany, British forces moved to Mersa Matruh and authorization was provided to form a mobile division in Egypt.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] In September 1938, due to the tensions between Britain and the Axis powers and a concern that Italy could invade Egypt, the Cairo Cavalry Brigade was ordered to Mersa Matruh.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The brigade consisted of the 7th Hussars equipped with light tanks, the 8th Hussars outfitted with trucks with the intent to be motorised cavalry, and the 11th Hussars with armoured cars.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Once there, the brigade was reinforced by the 1st Battalion, Royal Tank Corps, as well as artillery, engineers, medical, and logistical units and became known as the Mobile Force.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The assortment of different models of light tanks that the force had, lacked spare parts and the tank tracks had reached the end of their potential mileage capacity.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] For example, the 1st Battalion, Royal Tank Corps, had 63 light tanks but were quickly reduced to nine serviceable models.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] However, the historian Kenneth Macksey, a member of the Royal Armoured Corps during the Second World War, contended that it "might well have prevailed had the Italians" invaded Egypt, due to the armoured cars being in good working order and the Italian opposition consisting largely of tankettes.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] When tensions subsided, due to the Munich Agreement on 30 September, the force moved to Cairo where it was joined by is first infantry unit, the 1st Battalion, King's Royal Rifle Corps (1st KRRC).
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] In the meantime, on 27 September, Major-General Percy Hobart was reassigned from being the Director of Military Training and ordered to Egypt to form an armoured formation.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] He joined the Mobile Force after its arrival in Cairo in October, and it was used as the nucleus of the new division.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Theoretical and organisational work took place over the following months, before the first desert exercises were conducted in March 1939.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Field training was limited by vehicle shortages and tanks restricted on how many miles they could traverse due to the same issues that the Mobile Force had encountered six months prior.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] With desert training concluded, the formation returned to Cairo where indoor exercises were held over the summer, while the higher ranks examined and refined the division's administration and logistical issues and explored desert warfare principles.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] During 1939, the Mobile Division (Egypt) was renamed as the Armoured Division (Egypt), while the Cairo Cavalry Brigade became the Light Armoured Brigade (Egypt).
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The 7th Hussars were re-equipped with the Light Tank Mk VI, and handed over their old tanks to the 8th Hussars.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Additional armoured cars were delivered to the 11th Hussars, while the divisional artillery was provided with modern 25-pounder gun-howitzers.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] When tensions in Europe reached a boiling point, in late August and just prior to the outbreak of the Second World War in September, the division was again deployed into the Western Desert.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] In December, with Italy having not joined the war, the formation returned to Cairo to resume training.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The training conducted over the course of the year earned Hobart, and the division, the praise of his immediate superior, Major-General Richard O'Connor (commander, Western Desert Force), who stated it was the best trained formation he had ever seen.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Similar plaudits came from Lieutenant-General Henry Maitland Wilson (Commander-in-Chief British Troops in Egypt), O'Connor's superior.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] An exercise in October, however, resulted in a public reprimand for Hobart due to errors made.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] In November, Hobart was dismissed by General Archibald Wavell (Commander-in-Chief Middle East Command and who oversaw Wilson) and ordered back to the UK.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Major-General Michael O'Moore Creagh, the Inspector of the Royal Armoured Corps, was given command of the division on 4 December 1939 as Hobart's replacement.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Two months later, on 16 February 1940, further nomenclature changes took place.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The formation was renamed as the 7th Armoured Division, the Heavy Armoured Brigade (Egypt) became the 4th Heavy Armoured Brigade, and the Light Armoured Brigade (Egypt) was redesignated as the 7th Light Armoured Brigade.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The two armoured brigades dropped the heavy and light descriptives on 14 April.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] During April 1940, the War Office set out an organisation for armoured divisions that stated such formations should have 340 tanks.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] During this period, the 7th Armoured Division had just 65 cruiser tanks, with eight not equipped with their required anti-tank weapons.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The same month, the division started to return to Mersa Matruh.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Training continued for the majority, while the 11th Hussars moved close to the Frontier Wire on the Egypt-Libyan border, where they started reconnaissance of Italian positions.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The initial divisional insignia was similar to that used by the 7th Division during the First World War: A white circle, but on a red background rather than the First World War-era black background.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] In early 1940, the Jerboa (also known as a desert rat) was added to the design.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] While primarily red, the Imperial War Museum highlighted that pink variations may have existed.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The design was used on vehicles from its inception, but there is no evidence that it was worn on uniforms until at least 1943.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Then, only a single photograph depicts such and it is of the commanding officer.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] It is believed that the insignia was worn commonly on uniforms starting in 1944, and after the division arrived in the UK.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Most sources concur that the jerboa design was created during Creagh's tenure; that he felt something representative was needed to be added to the white circle and chose the desert rat.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] His wife then went to the Cairo zoo and sketched the first draft.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Rea Leakey, who was the division's intelligence officer (GSO 3) at the time, claimed in his memoir that he and Hobart conversed about his pet jerboa.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] When he informed Hobart that they were called desert rats, Hobart decided to use that as the nickname for the division.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] George Forty, who edited the memoir, included a contradictory note that disputed Leakey's version of events and explained the story surrounding Creagh and his wife at the zoo.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] On 10 June 1940, Italy entered the Second World War against the Allies.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] In response, the 1st KRRC, the 7th, and the 11th Hussars patrolled the border and then crossed into Italian territory the next day and took 70 prisoners.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The Italian border forts Capuzzo and Maddalena were quickly taken, and various small unit actions inflicted the loss of 24 armoured cars and several hundred casualties on the Italians.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The first tank-on-tank clash for the division occurred on 16 June, when a force of 12 Italian light tanks were engaged and destroyed.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] However, these actions did not hinder the Italian build-up, and they soon retook Capuzzo and engaged in their own reconnaissance efforts.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] While more of the division's tank units were initially moved forward, it was decided to avoid mechanical attrition and the majority were pulled back to the Mersa Matruh area.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] This left one tank regiment along with the 1st KRRC, joined by two additional infantry battalions, and several batteries from the division's artillery to monitor a 60 mi (97 km) section of the border.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Their instructions were to harass any Italian probes and to attempt to delay, but not become seriously engaged with, any offensive move.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The 11th Hussars were allowed to continue their long-range efforts into Italian territory.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Between 11 June and 9 September, 3,500 Italian casualties were inflicted for the loss of 150 of the division's personnel.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The tank strength of the division had also rose to 85 cruisers by September, although 15 were being repaired and wear and tear issues impacted the rest.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] On 13 September, the Italians invaded Egypt with a force of five divisions supplemented by a tank group.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] In accordance with their instructions, the division's forward elements engaged and harassed the Italians while falling back to avoid prolonged engagements.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] By 16 September, the Italians had reached Sidi Barrani.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] They halted to improve the infrastructure behind them and constructed a series of fortified camps.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The 7th Armoured Division regrouped at Mersa Matruh, then spent the following two months reconnoitering the Italian positions.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Towards the end of August, and prior to the Italian invasion, reinforcements and supplies were dispatched to Egypt from the UK.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] This included artillery, spare parts, and around 100 tanks for the division; a mix of light tanks and cruisers split between two armoured regiments.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Their arrival in early October doubled the 7th Armoured Division's strength.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] On 9 December, the Western Desert Force launched its counterattack.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The division protected the flank of the initial attack, then provided more direct support over the following days and assisted in the capture of a large number of Italian troops.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] They then pursued the Italians into Libya and took up position between Tobruk and Bardia.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] In January, as Bardia was captured, the division advanced on then encircled Tobruk.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] In February, with Italian forces in retreat across Libya, the division crossed the desert south of the Jebel Akhdar and captured Beda Fomm, south of Benghazi.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] On 7 February, as the tanks were unable to travel fast enough, the manoeuvre was led by an *ad hoc* brigade of armoured cars, towed artillery and infantry, which completed the trip in 30 hours, that cut off the Italian retreat and destroyed the Italian Tenth Army.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Lieutenant Colonel John Combe led this *ad hoc* group, which was known as "Combe Force" after him.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] After this, the tanks of the 7th Armoured Division, after eight months of fighting, needed a complete overhaul and the division was withdrawn to Cairo and temporarily ceased to be available as a fighting formation being replaced in the line by the 2nd Armoured Division.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Compass ultimately captured 130,000 Italians.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The Italians had proven so weak that Hitler was forced to send the Afrika Korps, under Erwin Rommel, as reinforcements.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] In April 1941, the Allied troops in Tobruk were cut off by the Germans and Italians.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] On 7 June, the division was again prepared for battle as part of Operation Battleaxe, having received new tanks and additional personnel.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] In the attack plan for Battleaxe, the 7th force was divided between the Coast Force and Escarpment Force.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] However, this Allied push failed, and the 7th Armoured Division was forced to withdraw on the third day of fighting.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] On 18 November, as part of Operation Crusader the whole of the 7th Armoured Division was concentrated on breaking through.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] They faced only the weakened 21st Panzer Division.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] However, the XXX Corps commander, Lieutenant-General Willoughby Norrie, aware that the 7th Armoured Division was down to 200 tanks, decided on caution.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] During the wait, in the early afternoon of 22 November, Rommel attacked Sidi Rezegh with the 21st Panzer and captured the airfield.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Fighting was desperate and gallant: for his actions during these two days of fighting, Brigadier Jock Campbell, commanding the 7th Support Group, was awarded the Victoria Cross.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] However, the 21st Panzer, despite being considerably weaker in armour, proved superior in its combined arms tactics, pushing the 7th Armoured back with a further 50 tanks lost (mainly from the 22nd Armoured Brigade).
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] On 27 June 1942, elements of the 7th Armoured Division, along with units of the 3rd The King's Own Hussars, suffered one of the worst friendly fire incidents when they were attacked by a group of Royal Air Force (RAF) Vickers Wellington medium bombers during a two-hour raid near Mersa Matruh, Egypt.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Over 359 troops were killed and 560 others were wounded.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The Western Desert Force later became HQ XIII Corps, one of the major parts of the British Eighth Army which, from August 1942 was commanded by Lieutenant-General Sir Bernard Montgomery.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The 7th Armoured Division, now consisting of the 22nd Armoured and 131st Infantry Brigades and commanded by Major General John Harding, fought in many major battles of the Tunisian Campaign, taking part in the Battle of El Agheila in December.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] By January 1943 the Eighth Army had reached Tripoli where a victory parade was held, with the 7th Armoured Division taking part.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Among the witnesses was Winston Churchill, the British Prime Minister, and General Sir Alan Brooke, the Chief of the Imperial General Staff (CIGS).
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The division, now commanded by Major General George Erskine after Harding was severely injured in January, next took part in the Battle of Medenine, followed by the Battle of the Mareth Line in March.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] In late April, towards the end of the campaign, the 7th Armoured Division was transferred to IX Corps of the British First Army for the assault on Medjez El Bab.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The fighting in North Africa came to an end just days later, with almost 250,000 Axis soldiers surrendering to the Allies and becoming POWs.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The division was not an assault force in the invasion of Sicily, instead remaining in Homs, Syria for training in amphibious warfare, but did participate in the early stages of the Italian campaign.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The 7th Armoured Division came ashore at Salerno, on 15 September 1943, to help repel heavy German counterattacks during the Battle for the Salerno beachhead (Operation Avalanche).
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The assembly of six battalions of a single regiment has since been considered a unique moment in the regiment's history.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The 169th Brigade was commanded at the time by Brigadier Lewis Lyne, who would later command the 7th Armoured Division from November 1944 onwards.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Used to fighting in the desert, the division had to adjust to the confined Italian roads.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The division crossed the river Volturno in southern Italy, constructing a pontoon bridge.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The 7th Armoured, handing over its battered vehicles and equipment to the recently arrived 5th Canadian (Armoured) Division, left Italy in late December 1943, arriving in Glasgow, Scotland in early January 1944.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] In November 1943, the division left Italy for the United Kingdom, with the last units arriving on 7 January 1944.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The division was re-equipped with the new Cromwell cruiser tanks and in April and May received 36 Sherman Vc Fireflies.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Each troop now had three 75 mm gun Cromwells and a 17-pounder gun Firefly.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The Desert Rats were the only British armoured division to use the Cromwell as their main battle tank.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The 22nd Armoured Brigade embarked on 4 June, and most of the division landed on Gold Beach by the end of 7 June, a day after the initial landings.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] 7th Armoured initially took part in Operation Perch and Operation Goodwood, two operations that formed part of the Battle for Caen.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] During Perch, the division was to spearhead one arm of a pincer attack to capture the city.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Due to a change in plan, elements of the division engaged tanks of the Panzer-Lehr-Division and the Heavy SS-Panzer Battalion 101 in the Battle of Villers-Bocage and were repulsed.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] After the Battle of the Falaise Gap, which saw most of the German Army in Normandy destroyed, the 7th Armoured Division then took part in the Allied advance from Paris to the Rhine.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The division's performance in Normandy and the rest of France has been called into question and it has been claimed they did not match those of its earlier campaigns.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] In early August 1944, Major General George Erskine, who had commanded the division since January 1943, Brigadier William Hinde, commanding the 22nd Armoured Brigade, and up to 100 other officers of the division were removed from their positions and reassigned.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Erskine was replaced as GOC by Major General Gerald Lloyd-Verney.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Historians largely agree that this was a consequence of the "failure" at Villers-Bocage and had been planned since that battle.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Historian Daniel Taylor is of the opinion that the battle's result provided an excuse and that the sackings took place to "demonstrate that the army command was doing something to counteract the poor public opinion of the conduct of the campaign".
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Historian and former British Army officer Mungo Melvin has commented approvingly of the 7th Armoured Division's institution of a flexible combined arms structure, which other British armoured divisions did not adopt until after Operation Goodwood.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The replacement of Erskine in August did not change the performance of the division.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] In November 1944, Lloyd-Verney was relieved by Major General Lyne, after he "was unable to cure the division's bad habits well enough to satisfy Montgomery and Dempsey".
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] There is almost no doubt that the division was suffering from collective and cumulative battle fatigue.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] As Lloyd-Verney put it, with some prescience: "There is no doubt that familiarity with war does not make one more courageous.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Following the advance across France, the division took part in the Allied advance through Belgium and the Netherlands, liberating Ghent on 6 September.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The division then took part in the advance to and securing of the River Maas, where the division, now commanded by Major-General Lewis Lyne, a highly experienced commander, was slightly reorganized, with many experienced men who had been overseas with the division for five years returning home.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] In January 1945 the division, with the 8th Armoured Brigade and 155th Infantry Brigade (from the 52nd (Lowland) Infantry Division) under command, took part in Operation Blackcock to clear the Roer Triangle.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The division had a short rest for training in late February.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] This was followed by Operation Plunder: the 7th Armoured Division crossed the River Rhine near Xanten and Wesel and advanced northeast.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] On 16 April 1945, the 7th Armoured Division liberated Stalag 11B in Fallingbostel, which was the first prisoner-of-war camp to be liberated.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The 7th Armoured Division's last action of the war was the battle for the German city of Hamburg.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] In July 1945 the 7th Armoured Division took part in the 1945 British victory parade in Berlin.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] Among the many witnesses of the parade were British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, who was particularly fond of the division, Field Marshal Alan Brooke, the Chief of the Imperial General Staff and Field Marshal Montgomery.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] During the summer of 1945, the BAOR reorganised and disbanded its corps headquarters.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] These were replaced by new formations based around a divisional headquarters.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] This resulted in the creation of the 7th Armoured Division District, which was headquartered at Bad Rothenfelde.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The division was reformed when Hannover District became the 7th Armoured Division.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] The division remained part of the BAOR until April 1958, when it was redesignated as the 5th Division.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] While the division ceased to exist, its traditions and iconic nickname were maintained by 7th Armoured Brigade.
[src:bermondsey/7th-armoured-division-united-kingdom] A monument to commemorate the 7th Armoured was erected at Brandon in Thetford Forest where the division trained prior to D-day.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] The **London Inner Ring Road**, or **Ring Road** as signposted, is a 12-mile (19 km) route with an average diameter of 2.75–5.5 miles (4.43–8.85 km), formed from a number of major roads that encircle Central London.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] The ring road forms the boundary of the London congestion charge zone, although the ring road itself is not part of the zone.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] The route is described as the *Inner* Ring Road because there are two further sets of roads that have been described as London ring roads.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] The North and South Circular Roads together form the second ring road around London, averaging 10–15 miles (16–24 km) in diameter.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] The M25 motorway is the outermost road encircling the metropolis, at an average diameter of 40–50 miles (64–80 km).
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] Plans for an Inner Ring Road were put forward by Patrick Abercrombie in the 1940s, in the County of London Plan.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] Construction of the New Road from Paddington to Islington began in 1756 to relieve congestion in the built-up area of London.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] At that time the districts of Marylebone, Fitzrovia and Bloomsbury were on the northern edge of the city, and only the southern parts of them had been built up.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] The New Road ran through the fields to the north of these three neighbourhoods.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] The road is now one of the busiest main roads in the city.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] It runs from Edgware Road in the west to Angel, in the east.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] After being renamed in 1857, the western section between Edgware Road and Great Portland Street is known as Marylebone Road, the central section between Great Portland Street and King's Cross is known as Euston Road, and the eastern section from King's Cross to The Angel is called Pentonville Road.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] City Road was constructed in 1761 to continue the route eastwards to the northern edge of the City of London.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] By far the greater portion of the road is in the London Borough of Islington but a small part near Kings Cross is in the London Borough of Camden, including an entrance to King's Cross St Pancras Underground station at the former King's Cross Thameslink station.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] Several halls of residence are located on Pentonville Road: Dinwiddy House (SOAS), Paul Robeson House and Nido Student Living.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] There are two green spaces along the road, Joseph Grimaldi Park and Claremont Square; the latter's central green area, however, is not open to the public.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] This street is distinguished by the "set back" housing lines originally intended to provide an atmosphere of spaciousness along the thoroughfare.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] It is one of the locations on the UK version of the Monopoly board game, which features areas native to London.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] Pentonville Road is one of the many London place names mentioned in the song "Transmetropolitan" by the Pogues.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] The road has an abundance of antique (or junk) shops along part of its length.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] There is also Bermondsey Square which holds an 'antique' market every Friday morning, usually known as *Bermondsey Market*, though officially as *New Caledonian Market*.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] Towards its southern end are a collection of shops, pubs and takeaways.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] Starting at the Elephant, Kennington Lane splits off from the A3 by means of a Y-junction, where Newington Butts becomes Kennington Park Road.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] The **Victoria one-way system** lies in front of Victoria station.
[src:bermondsey/a100-road-england] Clockwise, it includes Lower Grosvenor Place, Bressenden Place, and the west end of Victoria Street.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Thus Bermondsey need not have been an island as such in the Anglo-Saxon period, and is as likely to have been a higher, drier spot in an otherwise marshy area.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Bermondsey appears in the Domesday Book as *Bermundesy* and *Bermundesye*, in the Hundred of Brixton within the County of Surrey.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] It was then held by King William, though a small part was in the hands of Robert, Count of Mortain, the king's half brother, and younger brother of Odo of Bayeux, then earl of Kent.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Its Domesday assets were recorded as including 13 hides, 'a new and handsome church', 5 ploughs, 20 acres (8 hectares) of meadow, and woodland for 5 pigs.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] It also included interests in London, in respect of which 13 burgesses paid 44d (£0.18).
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The church mentioned in Domesday Book was presumably the nascent Bermondsey Abbey, which was founded as a Cluniac priory in 1082, and was dedicated to St Saviour.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Monks from the abbey began the development of the area, cultivating the land and embanking the riverside.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] They turned an adjacent tidal inlet at the mouth of the River Neckinger into a dock, named St Saviour's Dock after their abbey.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] But Bermondsey then was little more than a high street ribbon (the modern Bermondsey Street), leading from the southern bank of the Thames, at Tooley Street, up to the abbey close.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The Knights Templar also owned land here and gave their names to one of the most distinctive streets in London: Shad Thames (a corruption of "St John at Thames").
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Other ecclesiastical properties stood nearby at Tooley Street (a corruption of "St Olave's"), owned by the priors of Lewes, St Augustine's, and Canterbury, as well as the abbot of Battle.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] These properties are located within the Archbishop of Canterbury's manor of Southwark, where wealthy citizens and clerics had their houses.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] King Edward III built a manor house close to the Thames in Bermondsey in 1353.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The excavated foundations are visible next to Bermondsey Wall East, close to the famous Angel public house.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] As it developed over the centuries, Bermondsey underwent some striking changes.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] After the Great Fire of London, it was settled by the well-to-do, and took on the character of a garden suburb especially along the line of Grange Road and Bermondsey Wall East as it became more urbanised.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] A pleasure garden was constructed during the Restoration period in the 17th century, commemorated by the Cherry Garden Pier.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] A rare surviving building from this period is St Mary Magdalen Church in Bermondsey Street, completed in 1690 (although a church has been recorded on this site from the 13th century).
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] This church survived the 19th-century redevelopment phase and the Blitz unscathed.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] It is an unusual survivor for Bermondsey as buildings of this period are relative rarities in Inner London in general.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] In the 18th century, the discovery of a spring from the river Neckinger in the area led to the development of Bermondsey Spa, as the area between Grange and Jamaica Roads called Spa Road commemorates.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] A new church was built for the growing population of the area, and named St John Horsleydown.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Bermondsey was one of London's major industrial centres.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] It was the chief centre for the leather trade and tannery industry, food processing and manufacture, and the heart of the provisions trade in London.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Colloquially the area has been known as "larder of London", "biscuits town", and the "land of leather" reflecting the influence of these industries.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] While many of these industries have declined, their factories, warehouses and wharfs, and institutions remain significant in the area's built heritage and local landmarks, and are reflected in street and building names.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] It was from the Bermondsey riverside that the painter J.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Turner executed his famous painting of *The Fighting "Temeraire" Tugged to her Last Berth to be Broken Up* (1839), depicting the veteran warship being towed to Rotherhithe to be scrapped.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] By the mid-19th century factories sprang up, most notably the landmark factories of Alaska Factory (originally opened by fur merchants C.W.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Martin & Sons Ltd in 1869 for the processing of the Alaskan sealskin fur), Salt, cheese and Hartley's Jam.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Parts of Bermondsey, especially along the riverside, had become notorious slums with the arrival of industrial plants, docks and immigrant housing.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Saviour's Dock, known as Jacob's Island, was considered one of the worst slums in London.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] It was immortalised in Charles Dickens's novel *Oliver Twist*, in which the villain, Bill Sikes, meets his end in the mud of 'Folly Ditch', in reference to Hickman's Folly, which surrounded Jacob's Island.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Bermondsey vestry hall was built on Spa Road in 1881 but was severely damaged by bombing during the Blitz in 1941.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The original vestry hall was extended to create the Bermondsey Town Hall in 1930.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The area was extensively redeveloped during the 19th century and early 20th century with the expansion of the river trade and the arrival of the railways.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] London's first passenger railway terminus was built by the London to Greenwich Railway in 1836 at London Bridge.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The first section to be used was between the Spa Road Station and Deptford High Street.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The industrial boom of the 19th century was an extension of Bermondsey's manufacturing role in earlier eras.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] As in the East End, industries that were deemed too noisome to be carried on within the narrow confines of the City of London had been located here – one such that came to dominate central Bermondsey, away from the riverfront, was the processing and trading of leather and hides.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Many of the warehouse buildings from this era survive around Bermondsey Street, Tanner Street, Morocco Street and Leathermarket Street including the huge Leather Market of 1833 and the Leather, Hide and Wool Exchange of 1878; virtually all are now residential and small work spaces or offices.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Hepburn and Gale's tannery (disused as of early 2007) on Long Lane is also a substantial surviving building of the leather trade.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The Exchange building had a fine private club, effectively a gentlemen's club for the leading merchants and manufacturers.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] In 1703 they had acquired a royal charter from Queen Anne to gain a monopoly of trading and training of apprentices for within 30 miles (50 kilometres) of the ancient parish, similar to a City livery company, the Bermondsey tanners.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Peek, Frean and Co was established in 1857 at Dockhead, Bermondsey by James Peek and George Hender Frean.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] They moved to a larger plant in Clements Road in 1866, leading to the nickname 'Biscuit Town' for Bermondsey, where they continued baking until the brand was discontinued in 1989.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The former biscuit factory site was renamed as the Pearl Yard Bermondsey in 2025, and is being redeveloped into 1,600 new homes by Greystar.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Bermondsey, specifically Blue Anchor Lane, was also the location of the world's first food canning business, established in 1812, by Donkin, Hall and Gamble.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] During the Napoleonic Wars volunteer units were formed for home defence, including the 'Old' and 'New' Bermondsey Volunteers (existing in 1799) and the Rotherhithe Volunteers in 1803.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] After another invasion scare, the 10th (Bermondsey) and 23rd (Rotherhithe) Surrey Rifle Volunteer Corps were formed in 1860–61.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Together they became a volunteer battalion of the Queen's (Royal West Surrey Regiment) in 1883, with its drill hall in Jamaica Road.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] When the Territorial Force was created in 1908 this became the 22nd Battalion, London Regiment (Queen's).
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] After the outbreak of World War I in 1914 it expanded to three battalions, of which the 1/22nd served on the Western Front and the 2/22nd in Palestine.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Following the success of the recruitment campaign for 'Kitchener's Army' in 1914, Lord Kitchener asked the mayors of the Metropolitan boroughs of the County of London if they could raise more 'Pals battalions' drawn from their localities.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Despite Bermondsey already supporting the 22nd Londons, the Mayor and Borough Council agreed to form another infantry battalion, which became the 12th (Service) Battalion, East Surrey Regiment (Bermondsey).
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The men wore the coat of arms of Bermondsey as their collar badge.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] A number of them were recruited from the 'Black Hand Gang', a notorious Bermondsey street gang of the era, and they proved so skilful at Trench raiding that 'Black Hand Gang' became a nickname for the whole battalion.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Following World War I, the 12th East Surreys were disbanded and the 22nd Londons were reformed in the Territorial Army (TA).
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The London Regiment was abolished in 1937 and the battalion reverted to being the 6th (Bermondsey) Battalion, The Queen's.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] During World War II it again formed a second battalion, and both served in the Battle of France and North Africa.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The 1/6th was at the Battle of Alamein and then served with the 7th Armoured Division (the 'Desert Rats') in Italy and North West Europe, while the 2/6th were with the 56th (London) Division in Italy.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] In 1961 the 6th Queen's amalgamated with the other TA battalions of the Queen's Regiment.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] To the east of Tower Bridge, Bermondsey's 3+1⁄2 mi (5.5 km) of riverside were lined with warehouses and wharves, of which the best known is Butler's Wharf.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] They suffered severe damage in World War II bombing and became redundant in the 1960s following the collapse of the river trade.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] After standing derelict for some years, many of the wharves were redeveloped under the aegis of the London Docklands Development Corporation during the 1980s.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] They have now been converted into a mixture of residential and commercial accommodations and have become some of the most upmarket and expensive properties in London.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] In 1997, US President Bill Clinton and Prime Minister Tony Blair visited the area to dine at the Le Pont de la Tour restaurant at Butler's Wharf.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] At the same time more everyday housing was constructed in the areas north of the Old Kent Road, including several council estates.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Bermondsey was served by London's first railway, from Spa Road railway station, as part of the London Bridge to Greenwich line, and the junction of lines from Croydon and Kent at South Bermondsey.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] However, reorganisation of lines and temporary closure of stations left Bermondsey's transport links with the rest of London poorer in the late Twentieth Century.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] This was improved in 2000 with the opening of Bermondsey Underground station on the London Underground's Jubilee Line Extension and the East London Line extension as part of the London Overground.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The Blue serves as the central market place for Bermondsey as a whole.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Wee Willie Harris, known as "Britain's wild man of rock 'n' roll", came from Bermondsey and had worked as a pudding mixer at Peek Freans.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] He is usually credited as the first British rock and roll player.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The first 'Bermondsey' is that known as the location of an Anglo-Saxon monastery, and known from later charters to be the area around the post-Conquest Bermondsey Abbey and its manor, which was in turn part of the medieval parish.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] References in the Parliamentary Rolls describe it as "in Southwark".[] A later, Victorian civil parish of Bermondsey did not include Rotherhithe or St Olave's; this was the arrangement under the Metropolis Management Act 1855.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The Southwark parishes of St Olave's and St John's Horsleydown (the latter a 'daughter' of the former) with St Thomas's formed a parish union ('District Board of Works') known as 'St Olave's' from that date.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] This was the arrangement within the London County from 1889.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] In 1899 St Olave and St Thomas's District was created as a single civil parish and the next year, following London government reorganisation, this was merged with Rotherhithe and part of Deptford to form, with Bermondsey civil parish, the Metropolitan Borough of Bermondsey.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The Borough's first Mayor was Samuel Bourne Bevington (1832–1907), leather producer and one of the area's largest employers; his statue still stands in Tooley Street.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] This borough was incorporated into the London Borough of Southwark, in the Greater London reorganisation of 1965.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] For elections to the Greater London Council, Bermondsey was part of the Southwark electoral division until 1973 and then the Bermondsey electoral division until 1986.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Southwark London Borough Council has divided the borough into a number of community council areas.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The wards of London Bridge and West Bermondsey, North Bermondsey and South Bermondsey form the Bermondsey Community Council area.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Bermondsey's parliamentary representation has fluctuated with its population.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Since at least the 13th century, it had formed part of the Surrey County seat until the 1868 Reform Act when it became part of Southwark constituency.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] From 1885 to 1918, a separate Bermondsey constituency existed, which included part of the older Southwark constituency.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] 1918 saw the seat split between two new constituencies: Rotherhithe and Bermondsey West, both of which were in place until the 1950 general election when the old Bermondsey seat was recreated.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] In 1983, the area played host to a famous Bermondsey by-election in which Labour's Peter Tatchell lost the previously safe Labour seat to the Liberal Simon Hughes on a swing of 44%, which remains the largest by-election swing in British political history.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Hughes represented the area until 2015 when he was defeated by the Labour candidate Neil Coyle.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Millwall Football Club was originally formed in 1885, in Millwall on the Isle of Dogs, East London.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] They retained the name, even though they moved across the river to New Cross, South East London in 1910.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] In 1993 they moved to their current stadium, The Den.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The team has a strong local following, but has never been based in Bermondsey.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The stadium lies right on the border of Southwark, but falls under the Borough of Lewisham.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The nearest railway station is at South Bermondsey, which is a five-minute walk away.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] There are several railway stations in and around Bermondsey.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Bermondsey is in London Zone 2, but nearby London Bridge and Borough stations are in London fare zone 1.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Oyster Cards can be used for travel from stations in Bermondsey to other stations in the London region.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The Jubilee line passes through Bermondsey, calling at **Bermondsey** and **Canada** **Water** stations.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] **London Bridge** station on the Jubilee and Northern lines, and **Borough** on the Northern line are also nearby.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The Jubilee line provides a direct link from Bermondsey to Canary Wharf and Stratford in East London, and to Waterloo, the West End, Baker Street and north west London towards Willesden and Stanmore.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The Northern line from London Bridge links the area to Kennington, Clapham and Morden in the south west.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Northbound services travel through the City of London, King's Cross St Pancras and Camden Town, towards Edgware or High Barnet.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The East London line, South London line and South Eastern Main Line all pass through Bermondsey, providing frequent rail connections to Central London and South East England.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] London Buses routes 1; 42; 47; 78; 188; 381; C10 and P12 and night routes N1; N47; N199 and N381 all serve the Bermondsey and South Bermondsey area.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Bricklayer's Arms is a busy road junction between the London Inner Ring Road (A100/A202) and the A2, where routes from London Bridge meet with routes towards the East End, Surrey and Kent.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The southern portal of the Rotherhithe Tunnel (A101) is in Bermondsey.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The Tunnel was completed in 1908 and carries vehicle traffic from Bermondsey directly to the East End.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] In 2003, the Tunnel was rated the tenth most dangerous tunnel in Europe, owing in parts to its age and lack of safety features.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The London Borough of Southwark maintains most roads, particularly residential streets, but Transport for London (TfL) manages certain routes: the A100; the A101 (Rotherhithe Tunnel); the A2; the A200; the A202.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] The local authority say that vehicle exhaust fumes are the main source of air pollution in Southwark.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Roadside air pollution levels are monitored by the local authority in Bermondsey.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Results from 2017 suggest that Bermondsey has some of the highest nitrogen dioxide (NO2) levels in the Borough.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] All the above sites failed to meet national air quality objectives.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] A monitoring site on Old Kent Road registered an annual mean 22 μg/m-3 in 2017 for PM10 (particulates often found in exhaust), which meets national air quality objectives.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Bermondsey is well connected to the London and National Cycle networks, with several signed routes passing through the area.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] With several routes passing through Bermondsey, cycling infrastructure is maintained by both Transport for London (TfL) and Southwark Council.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Most routes run through Bermondsey in an east–west direction.
[src:bermondsey/bermondsey] Santander Cycles bicycle sharing was extended to the area in 2020 with five new docking stations, serving the Cycleway 4 route that will connect Tower Bridge and Greenwich.
